{"title_page": "Yael Grobglas", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Petra Salono\n| image              = Yael Grobglas at 2015 PaleyFest.jpg\n| caption            = Grobglas at the 2015 [[PaleyFest]] presentation for ''[[Jane the Virgin]]''\n| nationality        = Israeli\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1984|5|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| years_active       = 2004\u2013present\n| occupation         = Actress\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.yaelgrobglas.com}}\n| partner            = Artem Kroupenev\n| children           = 1\n}}\n'''Yael Grobglas''' ({{lang-he|\u05d9\u05e2\u05dc \u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05d2\u05dc\u05e1}}; born 31 May 1984) is an [[Israel]]i actress, best known for her roles as Petra Solano and her twin sister Ane\u017eka on [[The CW]]'s television series ''[[Jane the Virgin]]''.\n\nHer first major role was in three seasons of the Israeli sci-fi TV series ''Ha'i'' (English: The Island, 2007\u201309), which established her popularity among Israel's teenage audiences. She gained recognition for her debut film role in the first Israeli horror film ''[[Rabies (2010 film)|Rabies]]'' ({{lang-he|\u05db\u05dc\u05d1\u05ea}}, [[Transliteration|translit.]]&nbsp;Kalevet, 2010), which participated in the [[Tribeca Film Festival]], and a number of other venues internationally. Through 2010\u201311 Grobglas performed a number of lead and supporting roles in prime time Israeli television shows, including in the sitcom ''Ha-Shualim'' (English: The Foxes 2010), ''Ramzor'' (English: Traffic Light, Hebrew: \u05e8\u05de\u05d6\u05d5\u05e8), and ''Hatzuya'' (2011) (English: Split, Hebrew: \u05d7\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d4). Grobglas is also known for her role as \"The Girl\" in the interactive video of [[We the Kings]] \"Say You Like Me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wethekingsmusic.com/interactive/ |title=We The Kings 'Say You Like Me' Interactive Video |publisher=Wethekingsmusic.com |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref> and as Gabi in the popular Israeli series ''Tanuhi'' (Hebrew: \u05ea\u05e0\u05d5\u05d7\u05d9, English: Relax, 2012). It was announced on 22 February 2013 that the actress was cast in the lead role of \"America Singer\" in [[The CW Television Network|The CW's]] second pilot for ''[[The Selection]]'',<ref name=\"andreeva1\">{{cite news |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/02/cw-pilot-the-selection-casts-its-lead/ |title=CW Pilot 'The Selection' Casts Its Lead |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 19, 2013 |accessdate=February 23, 2013}}</ref> though that was ultimately not picked up as a television series. That same year, Grobglas was cast for [[The CW Television Network|The CW's]]'s ''[[Reign (2013 TV series)|Reign]]'' as Olivia, an Italian born noblewoman who is an old flame of [[Francis II of France|Prince Francis]] ([[Toby Regbo]]).<ref name=\"E-Online\">{{cite web |last=Bricker|first=Tierney |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/442863/reign-scoop-the-selection-s-yael-grobglas-cast-as-a-threat-to-the-throne/ |title=Reign Scoop: The Selection's Yael Grobglas Cast as a Threat to the Throne |work=[[E! News]] |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGrobglas was born in Paris. Her father Jean Pierre Grobglas is from a [[French-Jewish]] family, and of [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] ([[Polish-Jewish]]) descent.<ref>{{cite news |last=|first= |url=http://www.jpost.com/ArtsAndCulture/Entertainment/Article.aspx?id=83988 |title=A cast of castaways |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/yael-grobglas-662181/bio/ |title=Yael Grobglas |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4005920,00.html|title=mynet  \u05e8\u05e2\u05e0\u05e0\u05d4  - \u05d4\u05de\u05d4\u05e4\u05da \u05e9\u05dc \u05d9\u05e2\u05dc \u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05d2\u05dc\u05e1|author=|date=|work=ynet}}</ref> Her mother Eva (Rosner) is from Austria and she [[Conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]].<ref name=interview>{{cite web|url=https://www.studioact.co.il/ufksa7390/IfatExport(1).pdf |title=Bio |website=www.studioact.co.il |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>http://www.makorrishon.co.il/nrg/online/47/ART2/181/747.html</ref> In 1986, when Grobglas was two years old, the family [[Aliyah|immigrated]] to [[Israel]] and resided in [[Ra'anana]] city.\n\nHer talent and passion for performing arts became visible even as a young girl. As a teenager, Grobglas studied and performed in professional dance and ballet groups. She later lead a brief modeling career and participated in a number of runway shows and advertising campaigns. Eventually having realized a greater interest in acting, Grobglas graduated from the Yoram Loewenstein Performing Arts Studio in [[Tel Aviv]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 2007, Grobglas was cast to her first major role for the Israeli sci-fi series ''Ha'Yi'' (\"The Island\"), which made her popular among Israel's young audiences. Following two consecutive seasons of the show Grobglas enrolled in a full-time three-year acting program at the Yoram Loewenstein Performing Arts Studio. She completed the third season of ''Ha'Yi'' in 2010, and was cast for a number of major commercials during the course of her studies.\n\nIn 2010, Grobglas gained international recognition when she starred in the first Israeli horror film ''[[Rabies (2010 film)|Rabies]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/features/Rabies_Ahron_Keshales_and_Navot_Paposhaddo.html#.URLD-eh5P5Y |title=Tribeca Film Festival: '&#39;Rabies'&#39; |publisher=Tribecafilm.com |date=March 18, 2011 |accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref> (\"Kalevet\"). She was part of the main cast of the Israeli sitcom ''Ha-Shualim'' (\"The Foxes\"). Grobglas also played the role of Linda Christie in a [[Beersheba Theater]] adaptation of ''[[Play It Again, Sam (play)|Play It Again, Sam]]''.\n\nIn 2012, Grobglas was cast to the Israeli comedy-drama series ''Tanuchi'' (\"Chill\").\n\nIn 2013, Grobglas starred as America Singer in [[the CW]]'s [[The Selection#Television series and film adaptations|''The Selection'' pilot]],<ref name=\"andreeva1\" /> described as a cross between ''[[The Bachelor (U.S. TV series)|The Bachelor]]'' and ''[[The Hunger Games]]'', but it was ultimately not picked up to series.<ref name=\"andreeva2\">{{cite news |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie |title='The Selection' Dead At The CW |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/the-selection-dead-at-the-cw/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 9, 2013 |accessdate= }}</ref> In the same year, her roles included the lead in an Israeli film, and the recurring role of Olivia D'Amencourt in the CW's series ''[[Reign (2013 TV series)|Reign]]''.\n\nIn 2014,  Grobglas was cast as Petra, one of the main characters on the CW's ''[[Jane the Virgin]]''. When describing her experience as Petra to the New York Times, Grobglas said, \"I'm usually cast for the more goofy and tomboyish characters [...] I'm having a wonderful time playing someone so complex and layered and funny.\" \"She's calculating, resourceful and manipulative,\" she said. \"But even though I don't agree with the decisions she makes, you have to admire her. It's been a blast playing such a mischievous character because she's so unlike me.\"<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news |last=Shattuck |first=Kathryn |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/07/arts/television/fall-arts-preview-tvs-new-villains-hope-davis-john-carroll-lynch-yael-grobglas-and-others.html |title=So Good to Be Bad TV's New Villains: Hope Davis, John Carroll Lynch, Yael Grobglas and Others |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 3, 2014 |accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> In January 2015, Time Magazine stated that \"Grobglas [...] has turned Petra into one of television's most amusingly complex comic villains. Fans love to hate her, yet as Jane delves deeper into Petra's backstory \u2014 and shows off her lighter side \u2014 they're starting to love her as well.\"<ref name=\"TIME\">{{cite journal |last=Feeney|first=Nolan |url=http://time.com/3672757/jane-the-virgin-petra-solano-yael-grobglas/ |title=How Petra Solano Became Jane the Virgin's Most Lovable Villain |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=January 19, 2015 |accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref> In March 2016, TVLine gave Grobglas an honorable mention for her performance in ''[[Jane the Virgin]]'' Chapter 36: \"Leave it to Jane the Virgin's unsung MVP Yael Grobglas to turn the painful process of giving birth \u2013 to twins, no less! \u2013 into a comedic tour de force ... After witnessing Grobglas' impeccable ability to mix humor and emotion, we can't wait to see what challenges (and laughs) motherhood will bring for her character.\" <ref name=\"TVLince\">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/03/12/sarah-paulson-performance-american-crime-story-episode-6/|title=Performer of the Week: Sarah Paulson|date=March 12, 2016|website=[[TVLine]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Grobglas starred along [[Yon Tumarkin]] and [[Danielle Jadelyn]] in ''[[JeruZalem]]'', an English-language Israeli horror film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/images/3301834/hell-breaks-loose-jeruzalem-exclusive-first-look |title=Hell Breaks Loose In 'jeruZalem' (Exclusive First Look!) |website=Bloody-disgusting.com |date=July 7, 2014 |accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 2006, Grobglas has been in a relationship with Israeli businessman Artem Kroupenev, her high school sweetheart.<ref name=interview />\n\nOn September 22, 2019, Grobglas announced on Instagram that she was expecting her first child.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B2tLbR3Bal0/</ref> On January 17, 2020, she announced that she had given birth to a baby girl, Arielle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/yael-grobglas-welcomes-daughter-arielle/|title=Jane the Virgin's Yael Grobglas Welcomes First Child, Daughter Arielle: 'Wish Us Luck'|website=PEOPLE.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2007\n|''Ulai Hapa'am''\n|Toti\n|English title: ''Maybe This Time''\n|-\n|2007\u201309\n|''Hai''\n|Ginny\n|English title: ''The Island''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2010\n|''[[Rabies (2010 film)|Rabies]]''\n|Shir\n|Hebrew title: \u05db\u05dc\u05d1\u05ea (''Kalevet'')\n|-\n|''Ha'Shualim''\n|Eli\n|English title: ''The Foxes''\n|-\n|rowspan=4 |2011\n|''[[Ramzor]]''\n|Nufar Levy\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|''[[Split (TV series)|Split]]''\n|Noy\n|Recurring role (season 3)\n|-\n|''[[Bnot HaZahav]]''\n|Lihi\n|English title: ''Golden Girls''   \n|-\n|''Yehefim''\n|Jane\n|Miniseries, English title: ''Barefoot'' \n|-\n|2012 \n|''Tanuhi''\n|Gaby\n|English title: ''Chill''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2013\n|''The Selection''\n|America Singer<ref name=\"andreeva1\"/>\n|Unsold TV pilot<ref name=\"andreeva2\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Sabri Maranan (TV series)|Sabri Maranan]]''\n|Amit\n|Guest role; 2 episodes\nAdam's date\n|-\n|2013\u201314\n|''[[Reign (2013 TV series)|Reign]]''\n|Olivia D'Amencourt\n|7 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\u201319\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Jane the Virgin]]''\n|Petra Solano/Natalia Dv\u00f4racek\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Main Role; 98 episodes\n|-\n|Ane\u017eka Archuletta\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2015\n|''[[JeruZalem]]''\n|Rachel Klein\n|Film, Lead role\n|-\n|''[[HaPijamot]]''\n|Amit\n|English title: ''The Pajamas''\nRepeating her role from ''Sabri Marnan''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2016\n|''Grace Note''\n|Thea\n|Short film\n|-\n|''[[Crazy Ex-Girlfriend]]''\n|Trina\n|Episode: \"[[List of Crazy Ex-Girlfriend episodes#ep22|When Will Josh and His Friend Leave Me Alone?]]\"\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''\n|[[Psi (comics)|Gayle Marsh / Psi]]\n|2 episodes ([[List of Supergirl episodes#ep44|season 3]])\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[An Interview with God]]''\n|Sarah Asher\n|Film\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Hell's Kitchen (U.S. TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]''\n|Herself\n|Reality series; Guest diner; Episode: \"The Grand Finale\"\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n|''Play It Again, Sam''\n|Linda\n|Beersheba Theater\n|}\n\n===Music video===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2011\n|\"Say You Like Me\"\n|[[We the Kings]]\n|The Girl\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Yael Grobglas}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.yaelgrobglas.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|4141803}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grobglas, Yael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:French Jews]]\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli television actresses]]\n[[Category:Israeli film actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish Israeli actresses]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of French-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Ra'anana]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Paris]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:21st-century French actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Israeli actresses]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Yael Grobglas\n| image              = Yael Grobglas at 2015 PaleyFest.jpg\n| caption            = Grobglas at the 2015 [[PaleyFest]] presentation for ''[[Jane the Virgin]]''\n| nationality        = Israeli\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1984|5|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| years_active       = 2004\u2013present\n| occupation         = Actress\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.yaelgrobglas.com}}\n| partner            = Artem Kroupenev\n| children           = 1\n}}\n'''Yael Grobglas''' ({{lang-he|\u05d9\u05e2\u05dc \u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05d2\u05dc\u05e1}}; born 31 May 1984) is an [[Israel]]i actress, best known for her roles as Petra Solano and her twin sister Ane\u017eka on [[The CW]]'s television series ''[[Jane the Virgin]]''.\n\nHer first major role was in three seasons of the Israeli sci-fi TV series ''Ha'i'' (English: The Island, 2007\u201309), which established her popularity among Israel's teenage audiences. She gained recognition for her debut film role in the first Israeli horror film ''[[Rabies (2010 film)|Rabies]]'' ({{lang-he|\u05db\u05dc\u05d1\u05ea}}, [[Transliteration|translit.]]&nbsp;Kalevet, 2010), which participated in the [[Tribeca Film Festival]], and a number of other venues internationally. Through 2010\u201311 Grobglas performed a number of lead and supporting roles in prime time Israeli television shows, including in the sitcom ''Ha-Shualim'' (English: The Foxes 2010), ''Ramzor'' (English: Traffic Light, Hebrew: \u05e8\u05de\u05d6\u05d5\u05e8), and ''Hatzuya'' (2011) (English: Split, Hebrew: \u05d7\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d4). Grobglas is also known for her role as \"The Girl\" in the interactive video of [[We the Kings]] \"Say You Like Me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wethekingsmusic.com/interactive/ |title=We The Kings 'Say You Like Me' Interactive Video |publisher=Wethekingsmusic.com |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref> and as Gabi in the popular Israeli series ''Tanuhi'' (Hebrew: \u05ea\u05e0\u05d5\u05d7\u05d9, English: Relax, 2012). It was announced on 22 February 2013 that the actress was cast in the lead role of \"America Singer\" in [[The CW Television Network|The CW's]] second pilot for ''[[The Selection]]'',<ref name=\"andreeva1\">{{cite news |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/02/cw-pilot-the-selection-casts-its-lead/ |title=CW Pilot 'The Selection' Casts Its Lead |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 19, 2013 |accessdate=February 23, 2013}}</ref> though that was ultimately not picked up as a television series. That same year, Grobglas was cast for [[The CW Television Network|The CW's]]'s ''[[Reign (2013 TV series)|Reign]]'' as Olivia, an Italian born noblewoman who is an old flame of [[Francis II of France|Prince Francis]] ([[Toby Regbo]]).<ref name=\"E-Online\">{{cite web |last=Bricker|first=Tierney |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/442863/reign-scoop-the-selection-s-yael-grobglas-cast-as-a-threat-to-the-throne/ |title=Reign Scoop: The Selection's Yael Grobglas Cast as a Threat to the Throne |work=[[E! News]] |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGrobglas was born in Paris. Her father Jean Pierre Grobglas is from a [[French-Jewish]] family, and of [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] ([[Polish-Jewish]]) descent.<ref>{{cite news |last=|first= |url=http://www.jpost.com/ArtsAndCulture/Entertainment/Article.aspx?id=83988 |title=A cast of castaways |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/yael-grobglas-662181/bio/ |title=Yael Grobglas |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4005920,00.html|title=mynet  \u05e8\u05e2\u05e0\u05e0\u05d4  - \u05d4\u05de\u05d4\u05e4\u05da \u05e9\u05dc \u05d9\u05e2\u05dc \u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05d2\u05dc\u05e1|author=|date=|work=ynet}}</ref> Her mother Eva (Rosner) is from Austria and she [[Conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]].<ref name=interview>{{cite web|url=https://www.studioact.co.il/ufksa7390/IfatExport(1).pdf |title=Bio |website=www.studioact.co.il |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>http://www.makorrishon.co.il/nrg/online/47/ART2/181/747.html</ref> In 1986, when Grobglas was two years old, the family [[Aliyah|immigrated]] to [[Israel]] and resided in [[Ra'anana]] city.\n\nHer talent and passion for performing arts became visible even as a young girl. As a teenager, Grobglas studied and performed in professional dance and ballet groups. She later lead a brief modeling career and participated in a number of runway shows and advertising campaigns. Eventually having realized a greater interest in acting, Grobglas graduated from the Yoram Loewenstein Performing Arts Studio in [[Tel Aviv]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 2007, Grobglas was cast to her first major role for the Israeli sci-fi series ''Ha'Yi'' (\"The Island\"), which made her popular among Israel's young audiences. Following two consecutive seasons of the show Grobglas enrolled in a full-time three-year acting program at the Yoram Loewenstein Performing Arts Studio. She completed the third season of ''Ha'Yi'' in 2010, and was cast for a number of major commercials during the course of her studies.\n\nIn 2010, Grobglas gained international recognition when she starred in the first Israeli horror film ''[[Rabies (2010 film)|Rabies]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/features/Rabies_Ahron_Keshales_and_Navot_Paposhaddo.html#.URLD-eh5P5Y |title=Tribeca Film Festival: '&#39;Rabies'&#39; |publisher=Tribecafilm.com |date=March 18, 2011 |accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref> (\"Kalevet\"). She was part of the main cast of the Israeli sitcom ''Ha-Shualim'' (\"The Foxes\"). Grobglas also played the role of Linda Christie in a [[Beersheba Theater]] adaptation of ''[[Play It Again, Sam (play)|Play It Again, Sam]]''.\n\nIn 2012, Grobglas was cast to the Israeli comedy-drama series ''Tanuchi'' (\"Chill\").\n\nIn 2013, Grobglas starred as America Singer in [[the CW]]'s [[The Selection#Television series and film adaptations|''The Selection'' pilot]],<ref name=\"andreeva1\" /> described as a cross between ''[[The Bachelor (U.S. TV series)|The Bachelor]]'' and ''[[The Hunger Games]]'', but it was ultimately not picked up to series.<ref name=\"andreeva2\">{{cite news |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie |title='The Selection' Dead At The CW |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/the-selection-dead-at-the-cw/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 9, 2013 |accessdate= }}</ref> In the same year, her roles included the lead in an Israeli film, and the recurring role of Olivia D'Amencourt in the CW's series ''[[Reign (2013 TV series)|Reign]]''.\n\nIn 2014,  Grobglas was cast as Petra, one of the main characters on the CW's ''[[Jane the Virgin]]''. When describing her experience as Petra to the New York Times, Grobglas said, \"I'm usually cast for the more goofy and tomboyish characters [...] I'm having a wonderful time playing someone so complex and layered and funny.\" \"She's calculating, resourceful and manipulative,\" she said. \"But even though I don't agree with the decisions she makes, you have to admire her. It's been a blast playing such a mischievous character because she's so unlike me.\"<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news |last=Shattuck |first=Kathryn |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/07/arts/television/fall-arts-preview-tvs-new-villains-hope-davis-john-carroll-lynch-yael-grobglas-and-others.html |title=So Good to Be Bad TV's New Villains: Hope Davis, John Carroll Lynch, Yael Grobglas and Others |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 3, 2014 |accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> In January 2015, Time Magazine stated that \"Grobglas [...] has turned Petra into one of television's most amusingly complex comic villains. Fans love to hate her, yet as Jane delves deeper into Petra's backstory \u2014 and shows off her lighter side \u2014 they're starting to love her as well.\"<ref name=\"TIME\">{{cite journal |last=Feeney|first=Nolan |url=http://time.com/3672757/jane-the-virgin-petra-solano-yael-grobglas/ |title=How Petra Solano Became Jane the Virgin's Most Lovable Villain |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=January 19, 2015 |accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref> In March 2016, TVLine gave Grobglas an honorable mention for her performance in ''[[Jane the Virgin]]'' Chapter 36: \"Leave it to Jane the Virgin's unsung MVP Yael Grobglas to turn the painful process of giving birth \u2013 to twins, no less! \u2013 into a comedic tour de force ... After witnessing Grobglas' impeccable ability to mix humor and emotion, we can't wait to see what challenges (and laughs) motherhood will bring for her character.\" <ref name=\"TVLince\">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/03/12/sarah-paulson-performance-american-crime-story-episode-6/|title=Performer of the Week: Sarah Paulson|date=March 12, 2016|website=[[TVLine]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Grobglas starred along [[Yon Tumarkin]] and [[Danielle Jadelyn]] in ''[[JeruZalem]]'', an English-language Israeli horror film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/images/3301834/hell-breaks-loose-jeruzalem-exclusive-first-look |title=Hell Breaks Loose In 'jeruZalem' (Exclusive First Look!) |website=Bloody-disgusting.com |date=July 7, 2014 |accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 2006, Grobglas has been in a relationship with Israeli businessman Artem Kroupenev, her high school sweetheart.<ref name=interview />\n\nOn September 22, 2019, Grobglas announced on Instagram that she was expecting her first child.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B2tLbR3Bal0/</ref> On January 17, 2020, she announced that she had given birth to a baby girl, Arielle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/yael-grobglas-welcomes-daughter-arielle/|title=Jane the Virgin's Yael Grobglas Welcomes First Child, Daughter Arielle: 'Wish Us Luck'|website=PEOPLE.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2007\n|''Ulai Hapa'am''\n|Toti\n|English title: ''Maybe This Time''\n|-\n|2007\u201309\n|''Hai''\n|Ginny\n|English title: ''The Island''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2010\n|''[[Rabies (2010 film)|Rabies]]''\n|Shir\n|Hebrew title: \u05db\u05dc\u05d1\u05ea (''Kalevet'')\n|-\n|''Ha'Shualim''\n|Eli\n|English title: ''The Foxes''\n|-\n|rowspan=4 |2011\n|''[[Ramzor]]''\n|Nufar Levy\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|''[[Split (TV series)|Split]]''\n|Noy\n|Recurring role (season 3)\n|-\n|''[[Bnot HaZahav]]''\n|Lihi\n|English title: ''Golden Girls''   \n|-\n|''Yehefim''\n|Jane\n|Miniseries, English title: ''Barefoot'' \n|-\n|2012 \n|''Tanuhi''\n|Gaby\n|English title: ''Chill''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2013\n|''The Selection''\n|America Singer<ref name=\"andreeva1\"/>\n|Unsold TV pilot<ref name=\"andreeva2\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Sabri Maranan (TV series)|Sabri Maranan]]''\n|Amit\n|Guest role; 2 episodes\nAdam's date\n|-\n|2013\u201314\n|''[[Reign (2013 TV series)|Reign]]''\n|Olivia D'Amencourt\n|7 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\u201319\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Jane the Virgin]]''\n|Petra Solano/Natalia Dv\u00f4racek\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Main Role; 98 episodes\n|-\n|Ane\u017eka Archuletta\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2015\n|''[[JeruZalem]]''\n|Rachel Klein\n|Film, Lead role\n|-\n|''[[HaPijamot]]''\n|Amit\n|English title: ''The Pajamas''\nRepeating her role from ''Sabri Marnan''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |2016\n|''Grace Note''\n|Thea\n|Short film\n|-\n|''[[Crazy Ex-Girlfriend]]''\n|Trina\n|Episode: \"[[List of Crazy Ex-Girlfriend episodes#ep22|When Will Josh and His Friend Leave Me Alone?]]\"\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''\n|[[Psi (comics)|Gayle Marsh / Psi]]\n|2 episodes ([[List of Supergirl episodes#ep44|season 3]])\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[An Interview with God]]''\n|Sarah Asher\n|Film\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Hell's Kitchen (U.S. TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]''\n|Herself\n|Reality series; Guest diner; Episode: \"The Grand Finale\"\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n|''Play It Again, Sam''\n|Linda\n|Beersheba Theater\n|}\n\n===Music video===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2011\n|\"Say You Like Me\"\n|[[We the Kings]]\n|The Girl\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Yael Grobglas}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.yaelgrobglas.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|4141803}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grobglas, Yael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:French Jews]]\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli television actresses]]\n[[Category:Israeli film actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish Israeli actresses]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of French-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Ra'anana]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Paris]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:21st-century French actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Israeli actresses]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "name_user": "100.34.88.91", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yael_Grobglas"}
{"title_page": "Pathak", "text_new": "'''Pathak''' ({{lang-deva|\u092a\u093e\u0920\u0915}}) is a surname native to [[India]]. Pathak is mainly used by  [[Hindu]]  [[Brahmin]] communities of Northern and Western India, most prevalent in [[Punjab]], [[Kashmir]], [[Bihar]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Gujarat]],[[Uttarakhand]], [[Uttar Pradesh]],and [[Madhya Pradesh]]. However, it can also be found in [[Nepal]], [[Assam]] and [[Odisha|Orissa]].\n\n==Notable people==\nNotable people with the surname Pathak include:\n\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n* [[Amita Pathak]], Indian actress\n* [[Brajesh Pathak]] (born 1964), Indian politician\n* [[Bindeshwar Pathak]] (born 1943), Indian sociologist\n* [[Dina Pathak]] (1922\u20132002), Indian actor and director\n* [[Falguni Pathak]] (born 1964), Indian singer\n* [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]] (1896\u20131982), Vice President of India (1969\u20131974)\n* [[Harin Pathak]] (born 1947), Indian politician\n* [[Heera Pathak]] (1916\u20131995), Indian poet, literary critic, and wife of Ramnarayan\n* [[N. R. Pathak]] (1915\u20131985), Indian humanitarian, social worker, and politician\n* [[Parag Pathak]] (born 1980), Nepalese-American academic\n* [[Prashant Pathak]], Indo-Canadian investor, businessman and philanthropist\n* [[Raghunandan Swarup Pathak]] (1924\u20132007), Chief Justice of India\n* [[Ramnarayan V. Pathak]] (1887\u20131955), Indian poet, short story writer, and literary critic\n* [[Rameshwar Pathak]] (1938-2010), Indian singer\n* [[Ratna Pathak]] (born 1963), Indian actress\n* [[Riti Pathak]] (born 1 July 1977) is a member of the Lower House of Parliament in India from Sidhi     in Madhya Pradesh who belongs to Bharatiya Janata Party\n* [[Sabitri Bogati (Pathak)]], Nepalese politician\n* [[Shanta Pathak]] (1927\u20132010), British businesswoman\n* [[Shyam Pathak]], Indian actor\n* [[Supriya Pathak]] (born 1961), Indian actress\n* [[Surender Mohan Pathak]] (born 1940), Indian author\n* [[V. S. Pathak]]  (1926\u20132003), Indian historian and writer\n* [[Vijay Bahadur Pathak]], Indian politician\n* [[Vinay Kumar Pathak]], Vice Chancellor of Dr A.P.J.Abdul Kalam University, Lucknow\n* [[Vinay Pathak]] (born 1968), Indian actor\n*\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{surname|Pathak}}\n\n[[Category:Indian family names]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language surnames]]\n", "text_old": "'''Pathak''' ({{lang-deva|\u092a\u093e\u0920\u0915}}) is a surname native to [[India]]. Pathak is mainly used by  [[Hindu]]  [[Brahmin]] communities of Northern and Western India, most prevalent in [[Punjab]], [[Kashmir]], [[Bihar]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Gujarat]],[[Uttarakhand]], [[Uttar Pradesh]],and [[Madhya Pradesh]]. However, it can also be found in [[Nepal]], [[Assam]] and [[Odisha|Orissa]].\n\n==Notable people==\nNotable people with the surname Pathak include:\n\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n* [[Amita Pathak]], Indian actress\n* [[Brajesh Pathak]] (born 1964), Indian politician\n* [[Bindeshwar Pathak]] (born 1943), Indian sociologist\n* [[Dina Pathak]] (1922\u20132002), Indian actor and director\n* [[Falguni Pathak]] (born 1964), Indian singer\n* [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]] (1896\u20131982), Vice President of India (1969\u20131974)\n* [[Harin Pathak]] (born 1947), Indian politician\n* [[Heera Pathak]] (1916\u20131995), Indian poet, literary critic, and wife of