ad|1|fmt=sleader}} and<br />{{Representative|caad|5|fmt=sleader}}\n| leader_title3                   = [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]<!-- split between 1st and 4th districts --><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wedrawthelines.ca.gov/downloads/meeting_handouts_072011/handouts_20110729_q2_cd_finaldraft_splits.zip|title=Communities of Interest - City|publisher=California Citizens Redistricting Commission|accessdate=September 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930184128/http://wedrawthelines.ca.gov/downloads/meeting_handouts_072011/handouts_20110729_q2_cd_finaldraft_splits.zip|archive-date=2013-09-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| leader_name3                    = {{Representative|cacd|1|fmt=usleader}} and<br />{{Representative|cacd|4|fmt=usleader}}<ref>{{Cite GovTrack|CA|4|accessdate=March 2, 2013}}</ref>\n| established_title               = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n| established_date                = May 2, 1888<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calafco.org/docs/Cities_by_incorp_date.doc|title=California Cities by Incorporation Date|format=Word|publisher=California Association of [[Local Agency Formation Commission]]s|accessdate=August 25, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103002921/http://www.calafco.org/docs/Cities_by_incorp_date.doc|archivedate=November 3, 2014}}</ref>\n<!-- Area------------------>| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_06.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Aug 27, 2018}}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 7.20\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 7.18\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 0.03\n| area_total_km2                  = 18.66\n| area_land_km2                   = 18.59\n| area_water_km2                  = 0.07\n| area_water_percent              = 0.38\n| area_note                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = <ref>{{Cite GNIS|1657964|Auburn|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| elevation_ft                    = 1227\n| elevation_m                     = 374\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 13330\n| population_metro                = est. ~19,500 (including Foresthill, Applegate and Meadow Vista)\n| population_density_km2          = 752.99\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 1950.26\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|38|53|55|N|121|4|28|W|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n| timezone                        = [[Pacific Time Zone]]\n| utc_offset                      = -8\n| timezone_DST                    = PDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -7\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]s\n| postal_code                     = 95602-95604\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 530|530]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = {{FIPS|06|03204}}\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature IDs\n| blank1_info                     = {{GNIS 4|1657964}}, {{GNIS 4|2409754}}\n| website                         = {{URL|auburn.ca.gov}}\n| footnotes                       = {{gnis|1657964}}{{designation list|embed=yes|designation1=California|designation1_number=404}}\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| population_est                  = 14103\n}}\n'''Auburn''' is a city in and the [[county seat]] of [[Placer County, California]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=June 7, 2011|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|archivedate=May 31, 2011}}</ref> Its population was 13,330 during the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. Auburn is known for its [[California Gold Rush]] history, and is registered as a [[California Historical Landmark]].<ref name=CHL>{{cite ohp|404|Auburn|2012-10-11}}</ref>\n\nAuburn is part of the [[Sacramento metropolitan area]] and is home to the [[Auburn State Recreation Area]], the site of a number of sporting endurance events. Events include the [[Western States Endurance Run]]; the [[Western States Trail Ride]], also known as [[Tevis Cup]] Equestrian Ride; [[American River 50 Mile Endurance Run]]; American River 50 Mile Equestrian Ride; [[Way Too Cool 50 Kilometer]] Endurance Run; Auburn International Half Iron Triathlon; Auburn Century 100 Mile Bike Ride; Coolest 24 Hour Mountain Bike Race; Rio Del Lago 100 Mile Endurance Run; Sierra Nevada 50 Mile Endurance Run; and the Coolest Run: Ride & Tie.\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2011}}\n [[File:Auburn California courthouse.jpg|thumb|left| Placer County Courthouse was constructed between 1894 and 1898.]]\nArchaeological finds place the southwestern border for the prehistoric [[Martis people]] in the Auburn area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sagehen.ucnrs.org/CSFRS/petros.htm|title=NORTH FORK PETROGLYPHS|accessdate=August 15, 2008|author=Brauman, Sharon K.|date=October 6, 2004|publisher=ucnrs.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724171614/http://sagehen.ucnrs.org/CSFRS/petros.htm|archivedate=2008-07-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> The indigenous [[Nisenan]], an offshoot of the [[Maidu]], were the first to establish a permanent settlement in the Auburn area.\n\nIn the spring of 1848, a group of French gold miners arrived and camped in what would later be known as the Auburn Ravine. This group was on its way to the gold fields in [[Coloma, California]], and it included Francois Gendron, Philibert Courteau, and Claude Chana. The young Chana discovered gold on May 16, 1848. After finding the gold deposits in the soil, the  trio decided to stay for more prospecting and mining.\n\n[[Placer deposit|Placer mining]] in the Auburn area was very good, with the camp first becoming known as the North Fork Dry Diggings. This name was changed to the Woods Dry Diggings, after John S. Wood settled down, built a cabin, and started to mine in the ravine.  The area soon developed into a mining camp, and it was officially named Auburn in August 1849. By 1850, the town's population had grown to about 1,500 people, and in 1851, Auburn was chosen as the seat of [[Placer County]]. Gold mining operations moved up the ravine to the site of present-day Auburn. In 1865, the [[Central Pacific Railroad]], the western leg of the [[First Transcontinental Railroad]], reached Auburn, as it was being built east from [[Sacramento]] toward [[Ogden, Utah]].\n\nThe restored Old Town has houses and retail buildings from the middle of the 19th century.  The  oldest fire station and the Post Office date from the Gold Rush years. Casual gold-mining accessories, as well as American Indian and Chinese artifacts, can also be viewed by visitors at the Placer County Museum.\nAuburn was the home and birthplace of noted science fiction and fantasy poet and writer [[Clark Ashton Smith]]. A memorial to him is located near Old Town.\n\n==Landmarks==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Auburn statue.jpg|thumb|200px|Statue at the former Auburn Amtrak station honoring the 10,000+ Chinese workers (known then as \"Celestials\") who helped build the Central Pacific Railroad.]] -->\nAuburn is home to [[Placer High School]], which is one of the oldest high schools in California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://placer.puhsd.k12.ca.us/home/test/our-history|title=Our History - Placer High: Home of the Hillmen|website=placer.puhsd.k12.ca.us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nLocal dentist Kenneth H. Fox's colossal sculptures are located throughout the town. The statues chronicle Auburn's history, such as a middle-aged Claude Chana gold panning in the nearby American River, and a Chinese \"[[coolie]]\" worker building the Transcontinental Railroad.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Auburn-ca-geography.jpg|thumb|left|Rolling hills of Auburn, taken near Indian Hill Road.]]\nAuburn is located at {{Coord|38.898671|-121.074399|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|7.2|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|0.03|sqmi}}, or 0.38%, is water.\n\nAuburn is situated in the Northern California foothills of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] range, approximately 800 vertical feet above the confluence of the North Fork and Middle Fork of the [[American River]]. It is located between [[Sacramento]] and [[Reno| Reno, Nevada]] along [[Interstate 80]]. Mountainous wilderness canyons and the western slope of the Sierra Nevada lie adjacent eastward, while gentle rolling foothills well-suited for agriculture lie to the west. The crest of the Sierra Nevada lies approximately {{convert|45|mi|km}} eastward, and the Central Valley lies approximately ten miles to the west.\n\n==Climate==\nAuburn has a [[Mediterranean climate#hot-summer Mediterranean climate|hot-summer Mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Csa'') that is characterized by cool, moist winters and hot, dry summers. Average December temperatures are a maximum of {{convert|54.4|\u00b0F}} and a minimum of {{convert|39|\u00b0F}}.  Average July temperatures are a maximum of {{convert|94.0|\u00b0F}} and a minimum of {{convert|61.0|\u00b0F}}. Annually, there are an average of 59.4 days with highs of {{convert|90|\u00b0F}} or higher, an average of 7.0 days with {{convert|100|\u00b0F}} or higher, and an average of 17.1 days with {{convert|32|\u00b0F}} or lower.<ref name=\"nws.noaa.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://w2.weather.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=sto|title=National Weather Service - NWS Sacramento|publisher=Nws.noaa.gov|date=July 21, 2006|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref> The record high temperature was {{convert|113|\u00b0F}} on July 15, 1972. The record low temperature was {{convert|16|\u00b0F}} on December 9, 1972 and December 7, 2009.<ref name=\"nws.noaa.gov\" />\n\nAverage annual precipitation is {{convert|37.36|in|mm}}.  There are an average of 70 days with measurable precipitation.  The wettest year was 1983 with {{convert|64.87|in|mm}} and the driest year was 1976 with {{convert|11.76|in|mm}}.  The most precipitation in one month was {{convert|23.08|in|mm}} in January 1909.  The most precipitation in 24 hours was {{convert|5.41|in|mm}} on October 13, 1962,<ref name=\"nws.noaa.gov\" /> during the [[Columbus Day Storm]].  Snow rarely falls in Auburn; average annual snowfall is only {{convert|0.0-1.0|in|mm}}.<ref name=\"nws.noaa.gov\" />  The most snowfall in one year was {{convert|10.7|in|mm}} in 1972, including {{convert|6.5|in|mm}} in January 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?ca0383|title=AUBURN, CALIFORNIA - Climate Summary|publisher=Wrcc.dri.edu|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAuburn's K\u00f6ppen classification and climate similarities to locations such as [[Napa, California]] and parts of [[Italy]] make it a suitable region for growing wine [[grape]]s. Auburn and the surrounding areas of Placer County are home to over 20 [[winery|wineries]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wineries and Tours in Gold Country|url=http://www.visitplacer.com/wineries.aspx|website=www.visitplacer.com|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{{Weather box|width=1000px|\n|location = Auburn, California\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 75\n|Feb record high F = 78\n|Mar record high F = 86\n|Apr record high F = 98\n|May record high F = 107\n|Jun record high F = 110\n|Jul record high F = 115\n|Aug record high F = 110\n|Sep record high F = 111\n|Oct record high F = 102\n|Nov record high F = 87\n|Dec record high F = 76\n|Jan high F = 53\n|Feb high F = 60\n|Mar high F = 64\n|Apr high F = 71\n|May high F = 80\n|Jun high F = 88\n|Jul high F = 94\n|Aug high F = 92\n|Sep high F = 87\n|Oct high F = 77\n|Nov high F = 63\n|Dec high F = 54\n|Jan mean F = 46\n|Feb mean F = 51\n|Mar mean F = 54\n|Apr mean F = 60\n|May mean F = 66\n|Jun mean F = 73\n|Jul mean F = 78\n|Aug mean F = 76\n|Sep mean F = 73\n|Oct mean F = 65\n|Nov mean F = 54\n|Dec mean F = 47\n|Jan low F = 39\n|Feb low F = 42\n|Mar low F = 44\n|Apr low F = 48\n|May low F = 53\n|Jun low F = 58\n|Jul low F = 61\n|Aug low F = 61\n|Sep low F = 58\n|Oct low F = 52\n|Nov low F = 44\n|Dec low F = 39\n|Jan record low F = 21\n|Feb record low F = 23\n|Mar record low F = 27\n|Apr record low F = 33\n|May record low F = 36\n|Jun record low F = 43\n|Jul record low F = 48\n|Aug record low F = 46\n|Sep record low F = 41\n|Oct record low F = 31\n|Nov record low F = 27\n|Dec record low F = 16\n|Jan precipitation inch = 6.38\n|Feb precipitation inch = 6.3\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.83\n|Apr precipitation inch = 2.87\n|May precipitation inch = 1.57\n|Jun precipitation inch = 0.35\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.16\n|Aug precipitation inch = 0.08\n|Sep precipitation inch = 0.59\n|Oct precipitation inch = 2.09\n|Nov precipitation inch = 4.41\n|Dec precipitation inch = 6.73\n|year precipitation inch = 37.36\n|Jan snow inch = 0\n|Feb snow inch = 0.2\n|Mar snow inch = 0.2\n|Apr snow inch = 0.2\n|May snow inch = 0\n|Jun snow inch = 0\n|Jul snow inch = 0\n|Aug snow inch = 0\n|Sep snow inch = 0\n|Oct snow inch = 0\n|Nov snow inch = 0.2\n|Dec snow inch = 0.1\n|year snow inch = 0.9\n|source 1 = http://www.myforecast.com/bin/climate.m?city=11508&metric=false\n|date=June 2015 | source 2 = https://www.usclimatedata.com/climate/auburn/california/united-states/usca0054\n}}\n</center>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 814\n|1870= 800\n|1880= 1229\n|1890= 1595\n|1900= 2050\n|1910= 2376\n|1920= 2289\n|1930= 2661\n|1940= 5013\n|1950= 4653\n|1960= 5586\n|1970= 6570\n|1980= 7540\n|1990= 10592\n|2000= 12462\n|2010= 13330\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=14103\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010===\nThe [[2010 United States Census]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0603204|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140715025146/http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0603204|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 15, 2014|title=2010 Census Interactive Population Search: CA - Auburn city|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> reported that Auburn had a population of 13,330. The [[population density]] was 1,860.2 people per square mile (718.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of Auburn was 11,863 (89.0%) [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 100 (0.8%) [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 129 (1.0%) [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 240 (1.8%) [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 9 (0.1%) [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 405 (3.0%) from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 584 (4.4%) from two or more races.  [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1,331 persons (10.0%).\n\nThe Census reported that 13,052 people (97.9% of the population) lived in households, 145 (1.1%) lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 133 (1.0%) were institutionalized.\n\nThere were 5,759 households, out of which 1,502 (26.1%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 2,613 (45.4%) were [[marriage|opposite-sex married couples]] living together, 604 (10.5%) had a female householder with no husband present, 257 (4.5%) had a male householder with no wife present.  There were 352 (6.1%) [[POSSLQ|unmarried opposite-sex partnerships]], and 33 (0.6%) [[same-sex partnerships|same-sex married couples or partnerships]]. 1,845 households (32.0%) were made up of individuals and 801 (13.9%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.27.  There were 3,474 [[family (U.S. Census)|families]] (60.3% of all households); the average family size was 2.85.\n\nThe population was spread out with 2,645 people (19.8%) under the age of 18, 1,031 people (7.7%) aged 18 to 24, 2,898 people (21.7%) aged 25 to 44, 4,224 people (31.7%) aged 45 to 64, and 2,532 people (19.0%) who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 45.4 years. For every 100 females, there were 89.5 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.1 males.\n\nThere were 6,139 housing units at an average density of 856.7 per square mile (330.8/km\u00b2), of which 3,388 (58.8%) were owner-occupied, and 2,371 (41.2%) were occupied by renters. The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.0%; the rental vacancy rate was 6.5%.  8,017 people (60.1% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units and 5,035 people (37.8%) lived in rental housing units.\n\n===2000===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 12,462 people, 5,302 households, and 3,281 families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 1,690.2 people per square mile (652.9/km\u00b2).  There were 5,457 housing units at an average density of 740.1 per square mile (285.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 93.4% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 0.5% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.8% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 1.3% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 1.5% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.4% from two or more races. 6.0% of the population were [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 5,302 households out of which 28.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 38.1% were non-families. 31.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.31 and the average family size was 2.91.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 23.3% under the age of 18, 7.2% from 18 to 24, 25.7% from 25 to 44, 25.7% from 45 to 64, and 18.1% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 86.9 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 83.2 males.\n\nThe median [[income]] for a household in the city was $58,999, and the median income for a family was $82,250. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $36,258.\n\n==Transportation==\nAuburn is served by [[Amtrak]] passenger rail service a few times a day, and its [[Auburn (Amtrak station)|railroad station]] is the eastern terminus of AMTRAK's Californian ''[[Capitol Corridor]]'' train. [[Interstate 80 (California)|Interstate Highway 80]] is the main east-west highway through this area, connecting [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] to the west and the [[Lake Tahoe]]/[[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] areas to the east. This town can be reached through several interchanges on Interstate 80, three of which (exits 118, 119 A through C, and 120) are somewhat within the town limits. [[California State Route 49|California Highway 49]] is the main north-south highway through this area. Highway 49 connects Auburn with the towns of [[Grass Valley, California|Grass Valley]] and [[Nevada City, California|Nevada City]] to its north, and [[Placerville, California|Placerville]] to the south.\n\nThe [[Auburn Municipal Airport (California)|Auburn Municipal Airport]] is located three miles (5&nbsp;km) north of town, and it is a [[general aviation]] airport, only. Auburn owns and operates this airport and an industrial site. The airport site covers {{convert|285|acre|km2}} including an {{convert|80|acre|m2|adj=on}} industrial site. This airport has a single {{convert|3700|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}-long [[runway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auburn.ca.gov/dept/dept_airport.html|title=City of Auburn: Airport and Industrial Park|author=City of Auburn|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090909132857/http://www.auburn.ca.gov/dept/dept_airport.html |archivedate=September 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auburn.ca.gov/dept/dept_air_abt.html|title=City of Auburn: About the Airport|author=City of Auburn|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090909133035/http://www.auburn.ca.gov/dept/dept_air_abt.html|archivedate=September 9, 2009}}</ref> General aviation services are available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auburn.ca.gov/dept/dept_air_srvc.html|title=City of Auburn: Airport Services|author=City of Auburn|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090909133025/http://www.auburn.ca.gov/dept/dept_air_srvc.html|archivedate=September 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:2009-0724-CA-OldFirehouseAuburn.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Queen Anne style architecture in the United States|Queen Anne style]] Old Town Firehouse is a landmark.  It originally adjoined a row of commercial buildings (now demolished). It was home to the Auburn Volunteer Fire Department.<ref name=\"AuburnChamberFirehouse\">[http://www.auburnchamber.net/VISITINGAUBURN/HistoricalTour/OldTownFirehouse/tabid/123/Default.aspx Old Town Firehouse], Auburn Chamber of Commerce, Accessed August 1, 2009. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822010546/http://www.auburnchamber.net/VISITINGAUBURN/HistoricalTour/OldTownFirehouse/tabid/123/Default.aspx|date=August 22, 2009}}</ref>]]\n\nThe following [[film]]s were, at least in part, shot in Auburn:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.placer.ca.gov/Departments/CEO/EconDev/PlacerLTFilmOfc/ShotInPlacer.aspx |title=Placer Tahoe Film Office - Shot in Placer County |access-date=2009-02-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225124113/http://www.placer.ca.gov/Departments/CEO/EconDev/PlacerLTFilmOfc/ShotInPlacer.aspx |archive-date=2011-02-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (film)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]''\n*''[[Protocol (film)|Protocol]]''\n*''[[Breakdown (1997 film)|Breakdown]]''\n*''[[My Family (film)|My Family]]''\n*''[[The Phantom (1996 film)|The Phantom]]''\n*''[[Phenomenon (movie)|Phenomenon]]''\n*''[[Wisdom (film)|Wisdom]]''\n*''[[xXx (film)|xXx]]''\n*[[Cinema Verite (2011 film)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rosevilletoday.com/news/roseville/movies-filmed-in-placer-county/|title=Movies Filmed in Placer County|last=Staff|date=2019-01-06|website=Rocklin and Roseville Today|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref>\n*''[[The Ugly Truth (film)|The Ugly Truth]]''\n*Auburn is the town where George and Lennie were raised in [[John Steinbeck]]'s novel ''[[Of Mice and Men]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bernhard Museum Complex]]\n*[[Gold Country Museum]]\n\n==Books==\n*[http://worldcatlibraries.org/oclc/35563411&referer=brief_results Auburn, California: crossroads of historic gold country]. (1973). [S.l: s.n.].\n*Borchardt, G. A., Rice, S. J., & Taylor, G. C. (1980). [http://worldcatlibraries.org/oclc/7367466&referer=brief_results Paleosols overlying the Foothills fault system near Auburn, California]. Sacramento: California Division of Mines and Geology.\n*Barieau, C. (1988). [http://worldcatlibraries.org/oclc/18199045&referer=brief_results A self-guided walking tour to historic Auburn buildings: a guide to significant historical and architectural buildings of Auburn, California]. Auburn, Calif: Auburn Letter House.\n*Sanborn, D. (2001). [http://worldcatlibraries.org/oclc/45796288&referer=brief_results Chronology of Auburn, California]. Auburn, CA: Auburn Sesquicentennial Committee.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Auburn, California}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Auburn (California)|Auburn, California}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.yourauburn.com/ Auburn, CA - Information & Resources]\n*[http://www.auburnchamber.net/ Auburn Chamber of Commerce]\n\n{{clr}}\n{{Geographic Location\n|Center    = Auburn\n|North = [[North Auburn, California|North Auburn]]\n|Northeast = [[Foresthill, California|Foresthill]]\n|East = [[Cool, California|Cool]]\n|Southeast = [[Coloma, California|Coloma]]\n|South = [[Folsom Lake]]\n|Southwest = [[Penryn, California|Penryn]]\n|West = [[Lincoln, California|Lincoln]]\n|Northwest = [[Sheridan, Placer County, California|Sheridan]]\n|image     =\n}}\n\n{{Cities of Placer County, California}}\n{{Sacramento Valley}}\n{{Greater Sacramento}}\n{{California county seats}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Auburn, California| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Placer County, California]]\n[[Category:County seats in California]]\n[[Category:Cities in Sacramento metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Incorporated cities and towns in California]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1888]]\n[[Category:1888 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "64.52.135.213", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auburn,_Calif