{"title_page": "South Holyoke, Holyoke, Massachusetts", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = South Holyoke\n| settlement_type          = [[Holyoke, Massachusetts#Neighborhoods|Neighborhood of Holyoke]]\n| image_skyline            = Main Street, South Holyoke, Holyoke, Massachusetts.jpg\n| image_caption            = Commercial blocks on Main Street \n| image                    = \n| nickname                 = \n| motto                    = \n| pushpin_map              = USA Holyoke#USA Massachusetts#USA\n| pushpin_label_position   = \n| pushpin_map_caption      = \n<!-- location ------------------>\n| coordinates              = {{coord|42|11|48.2892|N|72|36|27.972|W|region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = \n| subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Massachusetts]]\n| subdivision_type2        = [[City]]\n| subdivision_name2        = [[Holyoke]]\n| subdivision_type3        = [[Ward (electoral subdivision)|Wards]] \n| subdivision_name3        = 1, 2\n| subdivision_type4        = [[Electoral precinct|Precincts]] \n| subdivision_name4        = 1A, 2A, 2B\n<!-- area ---------------------->\n| area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"maps\">Spatial analysis of {{cite web|url=http://www.holyoke.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/neighborhoods.pdf|title=Holyoke Neighborhoods|accessdate=3 Jun 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802205322/http://www.holyoke.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/neighborhoods.pdf|archive-date= 8 August 2017}}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi         = 0.26\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|id=609019|name=Highlands, Holyoke, Massachusetts|accessdate=3 Jun 2016}}</ref>\n|elevation_m              = 22\n|elevation_ft             = 72\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 01040\n|area_code                = [[Area code 413|413]]\n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = [[Massachusetts Historical Commission|MACRIS]] ID\n|blank1_info              = [http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=HLY.W HLY.W]\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''South Holyoke''' is a neighborhood in [[Holyoke, Massachusetts]] located approximately {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} south of the city center. Today the neighborhood contains many historical brick tenements and {{convert|165|acre|ha}} of mixed residential, commercial, and industrial zoning including many of the remaining businesses of the city's paper industry. The neighborhood is also home to the city's [[Nueva Esperanza (nonprofit)|Puerto Rican-Afro Caribbean Cultural Center]], the Carlos Vega and [[Valley Arena]] Parks, as well as the [[Holyoke Turner Hall]], one of the last remaining [[Turners|turnvereine]]s in New England, and the [[Holyoke Public Schools|William G. Morgan Elementary School]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hurricane season prompts Holyoke fundraisers to help Puerto Rican towns|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass|date=June 4, 2018|last=Plaisance|first=Mike|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/06/hurricane_season_prompts_fundr.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105004012/https://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/06/hurricane_season_prompts_fundr.html|archive-date=November 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Annette|last=Hofmann|chapter=Translating Gymnastics Into Economic and Political Power: The Rise and Decline of the German Turnverein in Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1871\u20131910|title=Turnen and Sport|pages=121\u2013147|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q__8CmcZBZMC|publisher=Waxmann M\u00fcnster|location=New York}}</ref> In 2018, South Holyoke had the highest percentage of renter-occupied housing of any neighborhood outside of Boston, with an average of 1.5% owner-occupied households across the neighborhood's two [[census block groups]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Planning Database|publisher=US Census Bureau|website=Research@Census|postscript=: Block Groups 250138115001, 250138115002|url=https://www.census.gov/research/data/planning_database/2018/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205193330/https://www.census.gov/research/data/planning_database/2018/|archive-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 210\n   | align = left\n   | footer = '''''Top to bottom:''''' Germania Mills in 1876, the builder of much of South Holyoke's early infracture; Main Street blocks at the corner of Cabot St, October 1941; \"Battleship Block\" as it appeared in 1978; Carlos Vega Park, dedicated 2012\n   | image1 = Germania Mills, Holyoke.jpg\n   | image2 = Main Street, South Holyoke, Massachusetts 1941.jpg\n   | image3 = Battleship Block, Holyoke, Massachusetts 1978 (colorized).jpg\n   | image4 = Carlos Vega Park, South Holyoke.jpg}}\nIn the mid-19th century the area was predominantly open land with some factories and [[brickyard]]s,<ref name=\"German\">{{cite book | last1=Wiesinger | first=Gerwart | title=Die deutsche Einwandererkolonie von Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1865\u20131920|trans-title=The German Immigrant Colony of Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1865\u20131920 |location=Stuttgart |language=German | year=1994 | publisher=F. Steiner Verlag | oclc=31941276 |page=61}}</ref> and was originally known as '''Tigertown''', as it hosted a number of baseball teams with one ''[[Boston Globe]]'' writer later attributing the name to the fact that \"local baseball men played for blood and showed such tigerish propensities toward rival teams if the game did not go to their liking\".<ref>{{cite news|work=Boston Sunday Globe|location=Boston|date=November 14, 1897|page=62|title=Holyoke; Mayor Smith Indorsed [sic] in the Caucuses\u2014 Old Names of Suburban Villages|quote=South Holyoke of today bears little resemblance to the 'Tigertown' of former days. In the days gone by the local baseball men played for blood and showed such tigerish propensities toward rival teams if the game did not go to their liking that perhaps this may have earned the cognomen of 'Tigertown.' A well-known baseball man recalls the feverish excitement which was developed whenever Springfield and Holyoye [sic] met on a ball field. It was invariably a gory battle, so much so that when Springfield came up here to play the local team, a squad of police, larger than the two ball nines, was required to bring the game to a peaceful ending}}</ref> In the earliest days, the players and attendees of these games as well as the settlers of the area were largely Irish, as one of the three early working class Irish settlements in Holyoke, rarely referred to as \"The Bush\", with others being \"The Patch\" in the downtown and \"The Flats\" to the north.<ref>{{cite book|oclc=786169259|title=American Cities in the Growth of the Nation|year=1957|last=Green|first=Constance McLaughlin|publisher=J. De Graff|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancitiesin0000gree/page/88 88]|url=https://archive.org/details/americancitiesin0000gree|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite book|title=History of St. Jerome's Parish, Holyoke, Massachusetts, Diocese of Springfield; issued in connection with the Observance of its Diamond Jubilee|year=1931|last=Lucey|first=P. J.|publisher=Diocese of Springfield|location=Holyoke, Mass.|oclc=42457185}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1890s these baseball fields had largely disappeared and the area became characterized by factories and worker housing, seeing influxes of different [[Germans in Holyoke|immigrant groups from Germany]]; with industrialist millwrights emigrating from [[Rhineland]] and about half of workers from [[Saxony]],<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131175125/https://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=189|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url=https://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=189|title=The German Component to American Industrialization (1840-1893)|website=Immigrant Entrepreneurship; German-American Business Biographies|publisher=German Historical Institute; German Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology}}</ref> by the 1875 it had the highest population, per capita, of German immigrants of any neighborhood or ward in New England, representing 88% of residents.<ref name=\"turnenNsport\">{{cite book|title=Turnen and Sport|editor=Annette R. Hofmann|chapter=Translating Gymnastics Into Economic and Political Power: The Rise and Decline of the German Turnverein in Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1871\u20131910|pages=121\u2013146|publisher=Waxmann M\u00fcnster|location=New York, M\u00fcnchen, Berlin|year=2004|author=Gerhard Wiesinger}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Islands of Deutschtum: German-Americans in Manchester, New Hampshire and Lawrence, Massachusetts, 1870-1942|publisher=P. Lang|year=1996|last=McCaffery|first=Robert Paul|page=72|quote=At one point the Germania [Mills] employed seventy-five percent of the Germans in Holyoke. The ward surrounding the Germania became eight-eight percent German, the highest German concentration of any New England City}}</ref> In subsequent decades this demographic would [[Americanize]] and dissipate, with other immigrant communities settling there from Canada, Greece, and Puerto Rico into the 20th century.<ref name=\"macris\">{{cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=HLY.W|title=MACRIS inventory record for The Flats - South Holyoke, Holyoke|publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts|accessdate=2014-06-18}}</ref> As of 2018, the neighborhood's residents were predominantly [[Puerto Ricans in Holyoke|Puerto Rican]], with the highest concentration of any such population in Holyoke or New England, representing 83.3% of residents.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206145757/https://statisticalatlas.com/place/Massachusetts/Holyoke/Ancestry|archive-date=February 6, 2019|url=https://statisticalatlas.com/place/Massachusetts/Holyoke/Ancestry|quote=South Holyoke [Ancestry map filtered to \"Puerto Rican\"]: 83.3%|publisher=Cedar Lake Ventures, Inc.|website=Statistical Atlas|title=Ancestry in Holyoke, Massachusetts (City)}}</ref> On December 10, 2019, as part of a $72 statewide initiative, Governor [[Charlie Baker]]'s administration announced a $6.56 million grant to support street, alley, and traffic infrastructure improvement in the neighborhood around Carlos Vega Park. The grant was part of a larger set of projects, including a mixed owner-renter housing development around the park to be funded and built by the [[Holyoke Housing Authority]], and capital infrastructure improvement by the [[Holyoke Water Works|Water Works]].<ref>{{cite web|website=MassWorks|publisher=Executive Office of Housing and Economic Development; Commonwealth of Massachusetts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210195750/https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-656-million-massworks-infrastructure-award-in-holyoke|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-656-million-massworks-infrastructure-award-in-holyoke|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces $6.56 Million MassWorks Infrastructure Award in Holyoke|date=December 10, 2019|author=Office of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|archive-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|title=The People of Holyoke; Great Proportion of Them Foreigners; What is Being Done for Their Americanization\u2014Forces of Law, Education and Example|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1902-11-09/ed-1/seq-28/|work=New-York Tribune|date=November 9, 1902|page=14|location=New York|via=Chronicling America, Library of Congress}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/SouthHolyokeNA/ South Holyoke Neighborhood Association]\n\n{{Holyoke, Massachusetts}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Holyoke, Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{HampdenCountyMA-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = South Holyoke\n| settlement_type          = [[Holyoke, Massachusetts#Neighborhoods|Neighborhood of Holyoke]]\n| image_skyline            = Main Street, South Holyoke, Holyoke, Massachusetts.jpg\n| image_caption            = Commercial blocks on Main Street \n| image                    = \n| nickname                 = \n| motto                    = \n| pushpin_map              = USA Holyoke#USA Massachusetts#USA\n| pushpin_label_position   = \n| pushpin_map_caption      = \n<!-- location ------------------>\n| coordinates              = {{coord|42|11|48.2892|N|72|36|27.972|W|region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = \n| subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Massachusetts]]\n| subdivision_type2        = [[City]]\n| subdivision_name2        = [[Holyoke]]\n| subdivision_type3        = [[Ward (electoral subdivision)|Wards]] \n| subdivision_name3        = 1, 2\n| subdivision_type4        = [[Electoral precinct|Precincts]] \n| subdivision_name4        = 1A, 2A, 2B\n<!-- area ---------------------->\n| area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"maps\">Spatial analysis of {{cite web|url=http://www.holyoke.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/neighborhoods.pdf|title=Holyoke Neighborhoods|accessdate=3 Jun 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802205322/http://www.holyoke.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/neighborhoods.pdf|archive-date= 8 August 2017}}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi         = 0.26\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|id=609019|name=Highlands, Holyoke, Massachusetts|accessdate=3 Jun 2016}}</ref>\n|elevation_m              = 22\n|elevation_ft             = 72\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 01040\n|area_code                = [[Area code 413|413]]\n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = [[Massachusetts Historical Commission|MACRIS]] ID\n|blank1_info              = [http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=HLY.W HLY.W]\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''South Holyoke''' is a neighborhood in [[Holyoke, Massachusetts]] located approximately {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} south of the city center. Today the neighborhood contains many historical brick tenements and {{convert|165|acre|ha}} of mixed residential, commercial, and industrial zoning including many of the remaining businesses of the city's paper industry. The neighborhood is also home to the city's [[Nueva Esperanza (nonprofit)|Puerto Rican-Afro Caribbean Cultural Center]], the Carlos Vega and [[Valley Arena]] Parks, as well as the [[Holyoke Turner Hall]], one of the last remaining [[Turners|turnvereine]]s in New England, and the [[Holyoke Public Schools|William G. Morgan Elementary School]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hurricane season prompts Holyoke fundraisers to help Puerto Rican towns|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass|date=June 4, 2018|last=Plaisance|first=Mike|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/06/hurricane_season_prompts_fundr.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105004012/https://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/06/hurricane_season_prompts_fundr.html|archive-date=November 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Annette|last=Hofmann|chapter=Translating Gymnastics Into Economic and Political Power: The Rise and Decline of the German Turnverein in Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1871\u20131910|title=Turnen and Sport|pages=121\u2013147|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q__8CmcZBZMC|publisher=Waxmann M\u00fcnster|location=New York}}</ref> In 2018, South Holyoke had the highest percentage of renter-occupied housing of any neighborhood outside of Boston, with an average of 1.5% owner-occupied households across the neighborhood's two [[census block groups]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Planning Database|publisher=US Census Bureau|website=Research@Census|postscript=: Block Groups 250138115001, 250138115002|url=https://www.census.gov/research/data/planning_database/2018/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205193330/https://www.census.gov/research/data/planning_database/2018/|archive-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 210\n   | align = left\n   | footer = '''''Top to bottom:''''' Germania Mills in 1876, the builder of much of South Holyoke's early infracture; Main Street blocks at the corner of Cabot St, October 1941; \"Battleship Block\" as it appeared in 1978; Carlos Vega Park, dedicated 2012\n   | image1 = Germania Mills, Holyoke.jpg\n   | image2 = Main Street, South Holyoke, Massachusetts 1941.jpg\n   | image3 = Battleship Block, Holyoke, Massachusetts 1978 (colorized).jpg\n   | image4 = Carlos Vega Park, South Holyoke.jpg}}\nIn the mid-19th century the area was predominantly open land with some factories and [[brickyard]]s,<ref name=\"German\">{{cite book | last1=Wiesinger | first=Gerwart | title=Die deutsche Einwandererkolonie von Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1865\u20131920|trans-title=The German Immigrant Colony of Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1865\u20131920 |location=Stuttgart |language=German | year=1994 | publisher=F. Steiner Verlag | oclc=31941276 |page=61}}</ref> and was originally known as '''Tigertown''', as it hosted a number of baseball teams with one ''[[Boston Globe]]'' writer later attributing the name to the fact that \"local baseball men played for blood and showed such tigerish propensities toward rival teams if the game did not go to their liking\".<ref>{{cite news|work=Boston Sunday Globe|location=Boston|date=November 14, 1897|page=62|title=Holyoke; Mayor Smith Indorsed [sic] in the Caucuses\u2014 Old Names of Suburban Villages|quote=South Holyoke of today bears little resemblance to the 'Tigertown' of former days. In the days gone by the local baseball men played for blood and showed such tigerish propensities toward rival teams if the game did not go to their liking that perhaps this may have earned the cognomen of 'Tigertown.' A well-known baseball man recalls the feverish excitement which was developed whenever Springfield and Holyoye [sic] met on a ball field. It was invariably a gory battle, so much so that when Springfield came up here to play the local team, a squad of police, larger than the two ball nines, was required to bring the game to a peaceful ending}}</ref> In the earliest days, the players and attendees of these games as well as the settlers of the area were largely Irish, as one of the three early working class Irish settlements in Holyoke, rarely referred to as \"The Bush\", with others being \"The Patch\" in the downtown and \"The Flats\" to the north.<ref>{{cite book|oclc=786169259|title=American Cities in the Growth of the Nation|year=1957|last=Green|first=Constance McLaughlin|publisher=J. De Graff|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancitiesin0000gree/page/88 88]|url=https://archive.org/details/americancitiesin0000gree|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite book|title=History of St. Jerome's Parish, Holyoke, Massachusetts, Diocese of Springfield; issued in connection with the Observance of its Diamond Jubilee|year=1931|last=Lucey|first=P. J.|publisher=Diocese of Springfield|location=Holyoke, Mass.|oclc=42457185}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1890s these baseball fields had largely disappeared and the area became characterized by factories and worker housing, seeing influxes of different [[Germans in Holyoke|immigrant groups from Germany]]; with industrialist millwrights emigrating from [[Rhineland]] and about half of workers from [[Saxony]],<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131175125/https://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=189|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url=https://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=189|title=The German Component to American Industrialization (1840-1893)|website=Immigrant Entrepreneurship; German-American Business Biographies|publisher=German Historical Institute; German Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology}}</ref> by the 1875 it had the highest population, per capita, of German immigrants of any neighborhood or ward in New England, representing 88% of residents.<ref name=\"turnenNsport\">{{cite book|title=Turnen and Sport|editor=Annette R. Hofmann|chapter=Translating Gymnastics Into Economic and Political Power: The Rise and Decline of the German Turnverein in Holyoke, Massachusetts, 1871\u20131910|pages=121\u2013146|publisher=Waxmann M\u00fcnster|location=New York, M\u00fcnchen, Berlin|year=2004|author=Gerhard Wiesinger}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Islands of Deutschtum: German-Americans in Manchester, New Hampshire and Lawrence, Massachusetts, 1870-1942|publisher=P. Lang|year=1996|last=McCaffery|first=Robert Paul|page=72|quote=At one point the Germania [Mills] employed seventy-five percent of the Germans in Holyoke. The ward surrounding the Germania became eight-eight percent German, the highest German concentration of any New England City}}</ref> In subsequent decades this demographic would [[Americanize]] and dissipate, with other immigrant communities settling there from Canada, Greece, and Puerto Rico into the 20th century.<ref name=\"macris\">{{cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=HLY.W|title=MACRIS inventory record for The Flats - South Holyoke, Holyoke|publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts|accessdate=2014-06-18}}</ref> As of 2018, the neighborhood's residents were predominantly [[Puerto Ricans in Holyoke|Puerto Rican]], with the highest concentration of any such population in Holyoke or New England, representing 83.3% of residents.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206145757/https://statisticalatlas.com/place/Massachusetts/Holyoke/Ancestry|archive-date=February 6, 2019|url=https://statisticalatlas.com/place/Massachusetts/Holyoke/Ancestry|quote=South Holyoke [Ancestry map filtered to \"Puerto Rican\"]: 83.3%|publisher=Cedar Lake Ventures, Inc.|website=Statistical Atlas|title=Ancestry in Holyoke, Massachusetts (City)}}</ref> On December 10, 2019, as part of a $72 statewide initiative, Governor [[Charlie Baker]]'s administration announced a $6.56 million grant to support street, alley, and traffic infrastructure improvement in the neighborhood around Carlos Vega Park. The grant was part of a larger set of projects, including a mixed owner-renter housing development around the park to be funded and built by the [[Holyoke Housing Authority]], and capital infrastructure improvement by the [[Holyoke Water Works|Water Works]].<ref>{{cite web|website=MassWorks|publisher=Executive Office of Housing and Economic Development; Commonwealth of Massachusetts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210195750/https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-656-million-massworks-infrastructure-award-in-holyoke|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-656-million-massworks-infrastructure-award-in-holyoke|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces $6.56 Million MassWorks Infrastructure Award in Holyoke|date=December 10, 2019|author=Office of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|archive-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|title=The People of Holyoke; Great Proportion of Them Foreigners; What is Being Done for Their Americanization\u2014Forces of Law, Education and Example|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1902-11-09/ed-1/seq-28/|work=New-York Tribune|date=November 9, 1902|page=14|location=New York|via=Chronicling America, Library of Congress}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/SouthHolyokeNA/ South Holyoke Neighborhood Association]\n\n{{Holyoke, Massachusetts}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Holyoke, Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{HampdenCountyMA-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Simtropolitan", "label": "safe", "comment": "moved {{Commons category}} from refs to externals", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Holyoke,_Holyoke,_Massachusetts"}
{"title_page": "Thame", "text_new": "{{hatnote|This is about the English town. For the Indian town,<!--sometimes 'Thame'--> see [[Thane]]. For the Nepali village, see [[Thame, Nepal]].}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{infobox UK place\n| official_name = Thame the reich\n| static_image_name = Thame Town Hall.jpg\n| static_image_caption = Thame Town Hall\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.75|-0.97|display=inline,title}}\n| os_grid_reference = SP710060\n| london_distance = {{convert|40|mi|0}}\n| label_position = bottom\n| area_total_km2 = 12.67\n| population = 11561\n| population_ref = (parish, with [[Moreton, Thame, Oxfordshire|Moreton]]) ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n| civil_parish = Nazi party\n| shire_district = [[South Oxfordshire]]\n| shire_county = [[Oxfordshire]]\n| region = South East England\n| country = Soviet Union\n| post_town = Thame\n| postcode_district = OX9\n| postcode_area = OX\n| dial_code = 01844\n| constituency_westminster = [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]]\n| website = [http://www.thametowncouncil.gov.uk/ Thame Town Council]\n}}\n\n'''Thame''' {{IPAc-en|t|e\u026a|m}} is a [[market town]] and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in [[Oxfordshire]], about {{convert|13|mi}} east of the city of [[Oxford]] and {{convert|10|mi}} southwest of the [[Buckinghamshire]] town of [[Aylesbury]]. It derives its name from the [[River Thame]] which flows along the north side of the town. The parish includes the hamlet of [[Moreton, Oxfordshire|Moreton]] south of the town. The [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] recorded the parish's population as 11,561.<ref>{{cite web |url= \nhttps://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=1170217835 |title=Thame Parish |work=nomis |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThame was founded in the [[History of Anglo-Saxon England|Anglo-Saxon era]] and was in the kingdom of [[Wessex]].\n\n==Abbey, parish church and prebendal==\n[[File:St Mary's Thame Geograph-3481538-by-Mark-Percy.jpg|thumb|left|St Mary the Virgin parish church]]\n[[Thame Abbey]] was founded in 1138 for the [[Cistercians|Cistercian]] Order: the abbey church was consecrated in 1145. In the 16th century [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] the abbey was suppressed and the church demolished. Thame Park (the house) was built on the site, incorporating parts of the abbey including the early-16th century [[abbot]]'s house. Its interior is one of the earliest examples of the [[Italian Renaissance]] in England. A [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] west wing was added in the 18th century. In about 1840 parts of the foundations of the abbey church were excavated: it was {{convert|77|yd}} long and {{convert|23|yd}} wide, with a [[Lady Chapel]] extending a further {{convert|15|yd}} at the east end.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|pp=809\u2013810}}\n\nThe earliest feature of the [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary the Virgin]] is the 12th century base of the [[Baptismal font|font]]. The font's octagonal bowl was re-cut in the 13th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=807}} The present church is a [[Cruciform#Cruciform architectural plan|cruciform]] building that was built in the 13th century. The [[chancel]] is [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]] and was built in about 1220, with six [[lancet window]]s in its north wall and presumably a similar arrangement in the south wall. It was twice altered in the next few decades: a three-light [[Tracery#Plate tracery|plate tracery]] window was inserted in its north wall in the mid-13th century and the five-light east window with geometrical tracery was inserted in about 1280. Whatever lancet windows may have been in the [[chancel]] south wall were replaced with three two-light [[English Gothic architecture#Decorated Gothic|Decorated Gothic]] windows with reticulated tracery, and a double [[piscina]] was added at the same time.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=806}}\n\nThe [[transept]]s and tower arches are also early 13th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|pp=806\u2013807}} The [[nave]] has five-[[Bay (architecture)|bay]] north and south [[Aisle#Architecture|aisles]] whose [[Arcade (architecture)|arcades]] were built in about 1260. The aisles were widened in the 14th century, when they acquired their Decorated Gothic windows and doors. The Decorated Gothic south porch has two storeys and a two-bay [[Rib vault|quadripartite vault]].{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=807}}\n\nThe [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]] [[clerestory]] is 14th or early 15th century. In the 15th century the tower piers were strengthened and the two upper stages of the tower were built. In 1442 the north transept was rebuilt with five-light Perpendicular Gothic north and east windows with panel tracery. At about the same time the south transept acquired similar windows and was extended eastwards to form a chapel with a 15th-century piscina. The Perpendicular Gothic nave west window was inserted in 1672\u201373, making it an example of [[Gothic Revival architecture#Survival and revival|Gothic survival]]. In 1838 the north aisle north wall was rebuilt under the direction of [[George Wilkinson (architect)|George Wilkinson]].{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=807}}\n\nThe [[Bell tower|tower]] has a [[Change ringing|ring]] of eight bells, all cast by Mears and Stainbank of the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] in 1876.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Thame&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=THAME |title=Thame S Mary V |last=Davies |first=Peter |date=8 December 2006 |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council for Church Bell Ringers]] |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Prebendary|Prebendal House]] is known to have existed by 1234,{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=812}} The Early English Gothic chapel was built in about 1250.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=814}} The [[Solar (room)|solar]] is also 13th century but was enlarged in the 14th, when the present [[King post|crown-post]] roof was added. The rest of the Prebendal House is dated from the 15th century. The hall is 14th century in plan but was later divided, and one part now has a fine 15th century roof. In 1661 the [[Antiquarian|antiquary]] [[Anthony Wood (antiquary)|Anthony Wood]] reported that the house was ruinous, and early in the 19th century the remains were in use as a farmhouse and barns. It was restored in 1836.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=813}} The Prebendal House was the home of singer/songwriter [[Robin Gibb]] and his wife Dwina from 1984, and Gibb is buried in St Mary's parish churchyard.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/may/21/robin-gibb-tribute-music |last=Stanley |first=Bob |authorlink=Bob Stanley (musician) |title=Robin Gibb: a tribute in words and music |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 May 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Social and economic history==\n[[File:School House, Church Row - geograph.org.uk - 583737.jpg|thumb|Entrance of the original grammar school building, completed in 1569]]\nIn 1550 the [[courtier]] [[John Williams, 1st Baron Williams of Thame]] built the [[almshouse]]s in Church Lane. He died in 1559, and his will established the local [[grammar school]]. Its original building, completed in 1569, stands next to the almshouses. In 1880 the school moved to its current premises in Oxford Road. In 1971 it became a [[comprehensive school]] under the name [[Lord Williams's School]].\n\nThe [[English Civil War|Civil War]] in the 1640s saw Thame occupied in turn by [[Cavaliers|Royalists]] and by [[Roundheads|Parliamentarians]]. After the [[Battle of Chalgrove Field]] in 1643, Colonel [[John Hampden]], who had been educated at the grammar school, died of his wounds at the house of Ezekiel Browne,{{sfn|Nugent-Grenville|1854|p=361}} later to become the Greyhound Inn. {{As of |2010}} some of Hampden's descendants still live in the town.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe champion [[Bare-knuckle boxing|bare-knuckle boxer]] [[James Figg]] was born in Thame in 1684 and had his early prize-fights at the Greyhound Inn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/pioneer/figg.html |title=James Figg|author=International Boxing Hall of Fame}}</ref> In the 21st century the Greyhound Inn was renamed the James Figg and in April 2011 the [[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]] unveiled a [[blue plaque]] there to commemorate him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/figg.html |title=James Figg 1684\u20131734 |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |work=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Thame Stribblehills southeast.jpg|thumb|Stribblehills, a 17th-century timber-framed house with [[brick nogging]]]]\nIn the 18th century many of the buildings in the boat-shaped High Street were re-faced with modern facades built of locally produced [[salt glaze pottery|salt glazed]] bricks. Late in the 18th century [[John Wesley]] preached in Thame. The congregation on that occasion was so large that the floor of the building gave way, and the crowd fell to the lower floor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thame.net/history.htm |work=Thame.Net |title=A History of Thame |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530022533/http://www.thame.net/history.htm |archivedate=30 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBy 1813 Thame had a [[workhouse]] in Wellington Street. In 1826 John Boddington, a miller who had been the proprietor of Thame Mill, became master of the workhouse.{{sfn|Lisle|2011|p=81}} In 1831 his son, also John Boddington, became a clerk at [[Strangeways Brewery]] in Manchester. A younger son, Henry Boddington, who had been born at Thame Mill in 1813, followed his brother and joined the same brewery in 1832. Henry became a partner in the business in 1847 and sole proprietor in 1853,{{sfn|Lisle|2011|p=83}} after which its beers were called [[Boddingtons]]. In April 2011 the Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board unveiled a blue plaque at the address of the former workhouse commemorating its association with Henry Boddington.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/boddington.html |title=Henry Boddington 1813\u20131886 |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |work=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]]}}</ref>\n\nThame [[Poor Law Union]] was established in 1835 and the following year a new workhouse designed by George Wilkinson was built on Oxford Road.<ref>[http://www.workhouses.org.uk/index.html?Thame/Thame.shtml Thame Poor Law Union and Workhouse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605230604/http://www.workhouses.org.uk/index.html?Thame%2FThame.shtml |date=5 June 2011 }}</ref> In the 20th century the building became the premises of Rycotewood College of [[Further education#United Kingdom|further education]]. In 2003 with two other colleges of further education to form Oxford and Cherwell College, now [[City of Oxford College]].\n\n[[Thame railway station]] was opened in 1862 as the temporary terminus of an extension of the [[Wycombe Railway]] from {{rws|High Wycombe}}. The extension was completed in 1864 when it reached {{rws|Oxford}}. In 1963 [[British Rail]]ways withdrew passenger services between {{rws|Princes Risborough}} and Oxford and closed Thame station, leaving Princes Risborough (7 miles) as the nearest passenger station until 1987 (see below)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadgauge.org.uk/oldsite/history/line-wycombe.html|title=The Wycombe Railway|accessdate=7 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223103017/http://www.broadgauge.org.uk/oldsite/history/line-wycombe.html|archivedate=23 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> BR dismantled the track between Thame and {{rws|Morris Cowley}}, but kept the line between Thame and Princes Risborough open for goods traffic to and from an oil depot in Thame.\n\nThame Town Hall was designed by the architect [[Henry James Tollit|HJ Tollit]] in [[Jacobethan]] style and built in 1888.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=809}}\n\nIn 1940 Willocks McKenzie, a local lorry driver, found a small hoard of late [[England in the Middle Ages|Medi\u00e6val]] coins and rings beside the River Thame. The coins were ten [[Groat (coin)|groats]] and the rings were five ornate examples ranging from the 14th to the 16th centuries. The county [[Coroner#England and Wales|Coroner]] declared them to be [[Treasure trove#England, Northern Ireland and Wales|treasure trove]] and therefore [[The Crown|Crown]] property. The Crown placed the hoard on permanent loan to the [[Ashmolean Museum]]. The most ornate ring was an ecclesiastical one incorporating a small [[reliquary]]. Its lid is decorated with a distinctive cross with two horizontal sections, similar to the [[Cross of Lorraine]]. Thame Town Council incorporated this cross into its town emblem.<ref>[http://www.thamehistory.net/topics/ThameHoard.htm Thame Local History, The Thame Hoard]</ref>\n\nIn 1974 the [[M40 motorway]] was extended from [[High Wycombe]] to Chilworth Farm at [[Great Milton]]. Junction 7 at [[Great Milton|Milton Common]] is about {{convert|3|mi|0}} southwest of Thame, giving the town a fast road link to London. In 1990 the M40 extension was completed, giving Thame a fast road link to [[Birmingham]].\n\nIn 1987 [[British Rail]] opened {{rws|Haddenham and Thame Parkway}} station at [[Haddenham, Buckinghamshire|Haddenham]], about {{convert|2|mi|0}} northeast of Thame, on the [[Chiltern Main Line]]. [[Chiltern Railways]] now provides passenger services linking the railway station to High Wycombe, {{rws|London Marylebone}}, {{rws|Banbury}} and {{rws|Birmingham Snow Hill}}. The station has a large car park, a taxi office, and regular buses into Thame.\n\nIn 1991 Thame oil depot closed, and BR dismantled the railway between Thame and Princes Risborough. [[Sustrans]] was allowed to re-use the former trackbed to create the [[Phoenix Trail]] which is part of [[National Cycle Network]] route 57. Reopening the rail line through Thame was an option considered by Chiltern Railways in their plan to open a direct rail route from London Marylebone to Oxford via Princes Risborough in 2015. The cost of reinstating bridges was considered prohibitive.\n\n[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] used Thame many times as a location for the ''[[Midsomer Murders]]'' drama series, representing the fictional town of Causton.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finding Causton |url= http://www.visitmidsomer.com/finding-causton/ |website=Visit Midsomer |accessdate=16 May 2018 |date=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nThe town's two largest employers, [[CPM Group]] and [[Travelodge UK|Travelodge]], both have their head offices on the edge of the town. [[W. Lucy & Co.]] moved its base from Oxford to Thame in 2005.\n\n==Public transport==\nSee above for details of Haddenham and Thame Parkway station. As of 2013 the fastest London Marylebone trains took 36 minutes.\n\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz Citaro BD12 DHK Thame TownHall wide.jpg|thumb|[[Arriva the Shires]] and Z&S buses at the stop outside Thame Town Hall]]\n[[Arriva the Shires]] [[Arriva Sapphire|Sapphire]] bus routes 280 and X8 link [[Oxford railway station]] and Aylesbury ''via'' Thame. Route 280 runs daily and serves [[Wheatley, Oxfordshire|Wheatley]] and [[Haddenham, Buckinghamshire|Haddenham]]. It runs every 20 minutes from Mondays to Saturdays and every 30 minutes on Sundays. Route X8 is an express service that bypasses Wheatley and Haddenham, used to run hourly on a Monday to Friday.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/GetTimetable/?guid=50bb8578-6607-47fb-bfa5-fcbf19118a0b&id=117114&date=180729-181206 |title=Sapphire \u2013 Aylesbury to Oxford via Haddenham (280), Thame and Wheatley (280) |publisher=[[Arriva Shires & Essex]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> From February 2019, the X8 only has 6 buses a day. 2 in the morning peak running from Aylesbury to Oxford and 4 in the evening peak running from Oxford to Aylesbury.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/beds-and-bucks/services/280-x8---sapphire---aylesbury-to-oxford/?direction=outbound |title=Sapphire \u2013 Aylesbury to Oxford via Haddenham (280), Thame and Wheatley (280) |publisher=[[Arriva Shires & Essex]] |accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Carousel Buses]] route 40 links Thame with High Wycombe ''via'' [[Chinnor]] and [[Stokenchurch]]. Services run hourly from Mondays to Saturdays. There is no Sunday or [[Bank holiday#In the United Kingdom|bank holiday]] service.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://assets.goaheadbus.com/media/cms_page_media/2018/2/6/Link40_Timetable_Leaflet_Feb2018-WEB.pdf |title=link40 |publisher=[[Carousel Buses]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016 [[Oxfordshire County Council]] ceased all bus subsidies. [[Buckinghamshire County Council]] still contracts operators to run subsidised bus routes, a few of which link local villages to Thame. They include route 110 operated by Redline Buses<ref>{{cite web |url= http://redlinebuses.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/T-110-Jul-17-1.pdf |title=Aylesbury - Chearsley - Long Crendon - Thame - Worminghall 110 |publisher= Z & S Transport |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> and routes 111, 112 and 113 run by Z&S Transport.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buckscc.gov.uk/media/1634/111.pdf |title=Oakley - Brill - Thame- Aylesbury 111\n |publisher=[[Buckinghamshire County Council]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buckscc.gov.uk/media/1635/112.pdf |title=Upper Winchendon - Oakley - Thame - Bishopstone - Aylesbury 112 |publisher=[[Buckinghamshire County Council]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buckscc.gov.uk/media/1636/113.pdf |title=Oakley - Thame - Longwick - Princes Risborough 113 |publisher=[[Buckinghamshire County Council]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Amenities==\n[[File:The Bird Cage Inn, Thame. - geograph.org.uk - 138013.jpg|thumb|Bird Cage, an early 16th-century public house]]\nThame has three primary schools: Barley Hill Primary School,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barley-hill.oxon.sch.uk/ |title=Barley Hill Primary School}}</ref> John Hampden Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.john-hampden.oxon.sch.uk/ |title=John Hampden Primary School}}</ref> and St Joseph's Catholic Primary School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-josephs.oxon.sch.uk/ |title=St Joseph's Catholic Primary School}}</ref> It has one county [[Secondary school#England and Wales|secondary school]], [[Lord Williams's School]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lordwilliams.oxon.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Home&pid=1 |title=Lord Williams's School}}</ref>\n\nThame is home to a wide variety of shops, pubs and restaurants.\n\nThame has a [[Women's Institute]],<ref>{{cite web |url= https://ofwi.weebly.com/list-of-wis.html |title=Alphabetical list of WIs |publisher=Oxfordshire Federation of Women's Institutes |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> a [[Rotary Club]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thame.rotaryweb.org/ |title=Thame Rotary Club}}</ref> and a [[Round Table (club)|Round Table]] club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thameroundtable.org/ |title=Thame & District Round Table}}</ref>\n\nThame hosts the Oxfordshire County and Thame Show, the largest one-day agricultural show in Britain.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thameshow.co.uk/ |title=Thame Show}}</ref> It used to be held on the third Thursday in September, the same day as the three-day Thame Fair opens in the town centre. On the day of the show local schools were closed. In 2010 the show was moved to the last Saturday in July. The organising committee have expressed a wish for the show to be a two-day event in the future.{{citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nIn October a smaller fair is held in the parking area in Upper High Street. In June the Thame Festival is held, which includes a carnival through the main streets, a flower festival, and a fete on the Southern Road recreation area. [[Peter Andre]] attended the Thame Carnival in 2011.\n\n[[File:The Spread Eagle Hotel, Thame - geograph.org.uk - 247563.jpg|thumb|Spread Eagle Hotel, built early in the 18th century]]\nBoth the [[Army Cadet Force|Army Cadets]] and the [[Air Training Corps]] have units in the town. 594 (Thame) Air Training Corps was formed in 1994, originally as a detached flight of 966 (Wallingford) Squadron. It became an independent unit in 1997, taking the number 594 Squadron.\n\nThame has community websites including Thame.\nnet<ref>[http://www.thame.net/ Thame.net]</ref> and Thame Hub.<ref>[http://www.thamehub.co.uk/ Thame Hub]</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n[[Chinnor R.F.C.|Chinnor Rugby Club]] is based at Thame. Its first XV currently plays in [[National Division One]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/chinnor/ |title=Chinnor RFC}}</ref> [[Thame United F.C.|Thame United Football Club]] first team plays in [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] Division One East<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thameunitedfc.demon.co.uk/ |title=Thame United FC}}</ref> Thame Town [[Cricket]] Club first eleven plays in [[Home Counties Premier Cricket League]] Division 2 West.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thametown.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp |title=Thame Town CC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714214303/http://thametown.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp |archivedate=14 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Thame has a [[bowls]] club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thamebowlsclub.co.uk/ |title=Thame Bowls Club}}</ref> and a tennis club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thametennisclub.co.uk/ |title=Thame Tennis Club}}</ref>\n  \n[[The Oxfordshire Golf Club]] is {{convert|1|mi|km}} southwest of Thame. The [[Golf course|course]] was designed by [[Rees Jones]] and has hosted tournaments including the [[Benson & Hedges International Open]] from 1996 until 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoxfordshiregolfclub.com/ |title=The Oxfordshire Golf Club}}</ref>\n\nThame Kickboxing Club, is part of the South East Academy and are based in the sports centre and have trained British, European and World Champions.\n\nThame Runners Club organises the popular Thame 10k each June, 33 years running.\n\n==Twinning==\nThame is twinned with [[Montesson]] in France and [[Sinaia]] in Romania.\n\n==Notable residents==\nViolinist [[Alfredo Campoli]] (1906\u201391) was married at St Joseph's Catholic Church in 1942 and retired to Thame in 1986.<ref name=Campoli>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/campoli.html |title=Alfredo Campoli 1906\u20131991 |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |work=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]]}}</ref> In April 2011 the Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board unveiled a blue plaque at 39 North Street to commemorate him.<ref name=Campoli/>\n\nEnglish film-maker and Internet personality [[Gavin Free]] (born 1988) and his co-host Daniel Gruchy lived in the town from 1992 until 2012. Free now lives in [[Austin, Texas]].<ref name=YouTube>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h9zOaPkyUIE |title=Where We Met |date=30 April 2016 |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Robin Gibb]] of the [[Bee Gees]] and his wife Dwina Murphy-Gibb lived in Prebendal House in Thame until his death in 2012. Robin's younger brother, [[Andy Gibb]], also lived with Robin in Prebendal House in Thame in the weeks before his death in 1988.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thame.net/archives/7767 |title=Thame says 'good bye' to Robin Gibb |work=Thame.net |date=8 June 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[BBC]] actor, announcer, executive [[Harman Grisewood]] (1908\u201397) was brought up at the Prebendal House in the 1910s and 1920s. It had a resident [[Catholic]] priest, Father Randolph Traill, who served in its chapel. In his autobiography, ''One Thing at a Time'' (1968), he described an outing with his brother, nanny, nursemaid and [[baby transport|pram]], when they were stoned by villagers as they approached the [[Church of England parish church]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thamehistory.net/places/Prebendal.htm |work=Thame History |title=The Prebendal}}</ref>\n\nPoet and playwright [[W. B. Yeats]] (1865\u20131939) lived in the town for a short time at Cuttle Brook House, 42 Lower High Street. His son was born there in 1921.<ref>{{cite web |title=Historic Thame Town Trail Factsheet |url=http://www.21stcenturythame.org.uk/files/99999126_THAME%20CENTRE%201%20for%20web.pdf |publisher=21st Century Thame |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902215044/http://www.21stcenturythame.org.uk/files/99999126_THAME%20CENTRE%201%20for%20web.pdf |archivedate=2 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A blue plaque commemorating him was unveiled in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Town unveils four blue plaques|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-13080925|accessdate=16 May 2018|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe composer [[Howard Goodall]] lived in Thame in the 1960s and 70s and, after leaving [[Stowe School]], attended Lord Williams's School.\n\nJonathan More and Matt Black, the duo who make up [[Coldcut]] both lived in Thame and attended LWS.\n\n[[Ronald Lee (cricketer)|Ronald Lee]], cricketer\n\n==See also==\n* [[Thame Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources and further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Aston |first1=Michael |author1-link=Mick Aston |last2=Bond |first2=James |title=The Landscape of Towns |series=Archaeology in the Field Series |year=1976 |publisher=[[J.M. Dent]] & Sons Ltd |place=London |isbn= 0-460-04194-0 |pages= 87, 89, 91, 96, 98 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Lisle |first=Nicola |date=October 2011 |work=[[The Oxford Times|Oxfordshire Limited Edition]] |title=The Master Brewer |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Newsquest]] |pages=81, 83}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Lobel |editor-first=Mary D |editor-link=Mary Lobel |year=1962 |title=A History of the County of Oxford |volume=7: Thame and Dorchester Hundreds |series=[[Victoria County History]] |place=London |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] for the [[Institute of Historical Research]] |pages=160\u2013219 |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Nugent-Grenville |first=George |authorlink=George Nugent-Grenville, 2nd Baron Nugent |year=1854 |title=Some memorials of John Hampden: his party and his times |place=London |publisher=[[Chapman & Hall]] |edition=Third, revised |page=[https://archive.org/details/somememorialsjo02nugegoog/page/n444 361] |url= https://archive.org/details/somememorialsjo02nugegoog |quote=John Hampden Thame. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Page |editor-first=W.H. |editor-link=William Henry Page |year=1907 |title=A History of the County of Oxford |volume=2: Ecclesiastical History, ''etc.'' |series=[[Victoria County History]] |place=Westminster |publisher=[[Archibald Constable]] & Co |pages=83\u201386 |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol2/pp83-86 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sherwood |first1=Jennifer |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Oxfordshire |year=1974 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |place=Harmondsworth |isbn=0-14-071045-0 |pages=806\u2013818 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Thame (England)|Thame}}\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.thame.net Thamedotnet]\n*[http://www.thamehub.co.uk/ Thame Hub]\n*[http://www.thamehistory.net/ Thame Local History]\n*[http://www.gracechurchthame.org.uk Grace Church Thame] \u2013 a [[Newfrontiers]] church\n*[http://www.barleyhillchurch.org.uk Barley Hill Church Thame]\n\n{{South Oxfordshire}}\n{{Oxfordshire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Thame| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:South Oxfordshire District]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|This is about the English town. For the Indian town,<!--sometimes 'Thame'--> see [[Thane]]. For the Nepali village, see [[Thame, Nepal]].}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|official_name= Thame\n|static_image_name= Thame Town Hall.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Thame Town Hall\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.75|-0.97|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference= SP710060\n|london_distance= {{convert|40|mi|0}}\n|label_position=bottom\n|area_total_km2=12.67\n|population= 11561\n|population_ref= (parish, with [[Moreton, Thame, Oxfordshire|Moreton]]) ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|civil_parish= Thame\n|shire_district= [[South Oxfordshire]]\n|shire_county= [[Oxfordshire]]\n|region= South East England\n|country= England\n|post_town= Thame\n|postcode_district= OX9\n|postcode_area= OX\n|dial_code= 01844\n|constituency_westminster= [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]]\n|website= [http://www.thametowncouncil.gov.uk/ Thame Town Council]\n}}\n\n'''Thame''' {{IPAc-en|t|e\u026a|m}} is a [[market town]] and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in [[Oxfordshire]], about {{convert|13|mi}} east of the city of [[Oxford]] and {{convert|10|mi}} southwest of the [[Buckinghamshire]] town of [[Aylesbury]]. It derives its name from the [[River Thame]] which flows along the north side of the town. The parish includes the hamlet of [[Moreton, Oxfordshire|Moreton]] south of the town. The [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] recorded the parish's population as 11,561.<ref>{{cite web |url= \nhttps://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=1170217835 |title=Thame Parish |work=nomis |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThame was founded in the [[History of Anglo-Saxon England|Anglo-Saxon era]] and was in the kingdom of [[Wessex]].\n\n==Abbey, parish church and prebendal==\n[[File:St Mary's Thame Geograph-3481538-by-Mark-Percy.jpg|thumb|left|St Mary the Virgin parish church]]\n[[Thame Abbey]] was founded in 1138 for the [[Cistercians|Cistercian]] Order: the abbey church was consecrated in 1145. In the 16th century [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] the abbey was suppressed and the church demolished. Thame Park (the house) was built on the site, incorporating parts of the abbey including the early-16th century [[abbot]]'s house. Its interior is one of the earliest examples of the [[Italian Renaissance]] in England. A [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] west wing was added in the 18th century. In about 1840 parts of the foundations of the abbey church were excavated: it was {{convert|77|yd}} long and {{convert|23|yd}} wide, with a [[Lady Chapel]] extending a further {{convert|15|yd}} at the east end.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|pp=809\u2013810}}\n\nThe earliest feature of the [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary the Virgin]] is the 12th century base of the [[Baptismal font|font]]. The font's octagonal bowl was re-cut in the 13th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=807}} The present church is a [[Cruciform#Cruciform architectural plan|cruciform]] building that was built in the 13th century. The [[chancel]] is [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]] and was built in about 1220, with six [[lancet window]]s in its north wall and presumably a similar arrangement in the south wall. It was twice altered in the next few decades: a three-light [[Tracery#Plate tracery|plate tracery]] window was inserted in its north wall in the mid-13th century and the five-light east window with geometrical tracery was inserted in about 1280. Whatever lancet windows may have been in the [[chancel]] south wall were replaced with three two-light [[English Gothic architecture#Decorated Gothic|Decorated Gothic]] windows with reticulated tracery, and a double [[piscina]] was added at the same time.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=806}}\n\nThe [[transept]]s and tower arches are also early 13th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|pp=806\u2013807}} The [[nave]] has five-[[Bay (architecture)|bay]] north and south [[Aisle#Architecture|aisles]] whose [[Arcade (architecture)|arcades]] were built in about 1260. The aisles were widened in the 14th century, when they acquired their Decorated Gothic windows and doors. The Decorated Gothic south porch has two storeys and a two-bay [[Rib vault|quadripartite vault]].{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=807}}\n\nThe [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]] [[clerestory]] is 14th or early 15th century. In the 15th century the tower piers were strengthened and the two upper stages of the tower were built. In 1442 the north transept was rebuilt with five-light Perpendicular Gothic north and east windows with panel tracery. At about the same time the south transept acquired similar windows and was extended eastwards to form a chapel with a 15th-century piscina. The Perpendicular Gothic nave west window was inserted in 1672\u201373, making it an example of [[Gothic Revival architecture#Survival and revival|Gothic survival]]. In 1838 the north aisle north wall was rebuilt under the direction of [[George Wilkinson (architect)|George Wilkinson]].{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=807}}\n\nThe [[Bell tower|tower]] has a [[Change ringing|ring]] of eight bells, all cast by Mears and Stainbank of the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] in 1876.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Thame&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=THAME |title=Thame S Mary V |last=Davies |first=Peter |date=8 December 2006 |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council for Church Bell Ringers]] |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Prebendary|Prebendal House]] is known to have existed by 1234,{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=812}} The Early English Gothic chapel was built in about 1250.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=814}} The [[Solar (room)|solar]] is also 13th century but was enlarged in the 14th, when the present [[King post|crown-post]] roof was added. The rest of the Prebendal House is dated from the 15th century. The hall is 14th century in plan but was later divided, and one part now has a fine 15th century roof. In 1661 the [[Antiquarian|antiquary]] [[Anthony Wood (antiquary)|Anthony Wood]] reported that the house was ruinous, and early in the 19th century the remains were in use as a farmhouse and barns. It was restored in 1836.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=813}} The Prebendal House was the home of singer/songwriter [[Robin Gibb]] and his wife Dwina from 1984, and Gibb is buried in St Mary's parish churchyard.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/may/21/robin-gibb-tribute-music |last=Stanley |first=Bob |authorlink=Bob Stanley (musician) |title=Robin Gibb: a tribute in words and music |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 May 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Social and economic history==\n[[File:School House, Church Row - geograph.org.uk - 583737.jpg|thumb|Entrance of the original grammar school building, completed in 1569]]\nIn 1550 the [[courtier]] [[John Williams, 1st Baron Williams of Thame]] built the [[almshouse]]s in Church Lane. He died in 1559, and his will established the local [[grammar school]]. Its original building, completed in 1569, stands next to the almshouses. In 1880 the school moved to its current premises in Oxford Road. In 1971 it became a [[comprehensive school]] under the name [[Lord Williams's School]].\n\nThe [[English Civil War|Civil War]] in the 1640s saw Thame occupied in turn by [[Cavaliers|Royalists]] and by [[Roundheads|Parliamentarians]]. After the [[Battle of Chalgrove Field]] in 1643, Colonel [[John Hampden]], who had been educated at the grammar school, died of his wounds at the house of Ezekiel Browne,{{sfn|Nugent-Grenville|1854|p=361}} later to become the Greyhound Inn. {{As of |2010}} some of Hampden's descendants still live in the town.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe champion [[Bare-knuckle boxing|bare-knuckle boxer]] [[James Figg]] was born in Thame in 1684 and had his early prize-fights at the Greyhound Inn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/pioneer/figg.html |title=James Figg|author=International Boxing Hall of Fame}}</ref> In the 21st century the Greyhound Inn was renamed the James Figg and in April 2011 the [[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]] unveiled a [[blue plaque]] there to commemorate him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/figg.html |title=James Figg 1684\u20131734 |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |work=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Thame Stribblehills southeast.jpg|thumb|Stribblehills, a 17th-century timber-framed house with [[brick nogging]]]]\nIn the 18th century many of the buildings in the boat-shaped High Street were re-faced with modern facades built of locally produced [[salt glaze pottery|salt glazed]] bricks. Late in the 18th century [[John Wesley]] preached in Thame. The congregation on that occasion was so large that the floor of the building gave way, and the crowd fell to the lower floor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thame.net/history.htm |work=Thame.Net |title=A History of Thame |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530022533/http://www.thame.net/history.htm |archivedate=30 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBy 1813 Thame had a [[workhouse]] in Wellington Street. In 1826 John Boddington, a miller who had been the proprietor of Thame Mill, became master of the workhouse.{{sfn|Lisle|2011|p=81}} In 1831 his son, also John Boddington, became a clerk at [[Strangeways Brewery]] in Manchester. A younger son, Henry Boddington, who had been born at Thame Mill in 1813, followed his brother and joined the same brewery in 1832. Henry became a partner in the business in 1847 and sole proprietor in 1853,{{sfn|Lisle|2011|p=83}} after which its beers were called [[Boddingtons]]. In April 2011 the Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board unveiled a blue plaque at the address of the former workhouse commemorating its association with Henry Boddington.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/boddington.html |title=Henry Boddington 1813\u20131886 |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |work=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]]}}</ref>\n\nThame [[Poor Law Union]] was established in 1835 and the following year a new workhouse designed by George Wilkinson was built on Oxford Road.<ref>[http://www.workhouses.org.uk/index.html?Thame/Thame.shtml Thame Poor Law Union and Workhouse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605230604/http://www.workhouses.org.uk/index.html?Thame%2FThame.shtml |date=5 June 2011 }}</ref> In the 20th century the building became the premises of Rycotewood College of [[Further education#United Kingdom|further education]]. In 2003 with two other colleges of further education to form Oxford and Cherwell College, now [[City of Oxford College]].\n\n[[Thame railway station]] was opened in 1862 as the temporary terminus of an extension of the [[Wycombe Railway]] from {{rws|High Wycombe}}. The extension was completed in 1864 when it reached {{rws|Oxford}}. In 1963 [[British Rail]]ways withdrew passenger services between {{rws|Princes Risborough}} and Oxford and closed Thame station, leaving Princes Risborough (7 miles) as the nearest passenger station until 1987 (see below)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadgauge.org.uk/oldsite/history/line-wycombe.html|title=The Wycombe Railway|accessdate=7 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223103017/http://www.broadgauge.org.uk/oldsite/history/line-wycombe.html|archivedate=23 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> BR dismantled the track between Thame and {{rws|Morris Cowley}}, but kept the line between Thame and Princes Risborough open for goods traffic to and from an oil depot in Thame.\n\nThame Town Hall was designed by the architect [[Henry James Tollit|HJ Tollit]] in [[Jacobethan]] style and built in 1888.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=809}}\n\nIn 1940 Willocks McKenzie, a local lorry driver, found a small hoard of late [[England in the Middle Ages|Medi\u00e6val]] coins and rings beside the River Thame. The coins were ten [[Groat (coin)|groats]] and the rings were five ornate examples ranging from the 14th to the 16th centuries. The county [[Coroner#England and Wales|Coroner]] declared them to be [[Treasure trove#England, Northern Ireland and Wales|treasure trove]] and therefore [[The Crown|Crown]] property. The Crown placed the hoard on permanent loan to the [[Ashmolean Museum]]. The most ornate ring was an ecclesiastical one incorporating a small [[reliquary]]. Its lid is decorated with a distinctive cross with two horizontal sections, similar to the [[Cross of Lorraine]]. Thame Town Council incorporated this cross into its town emblem.<ref>[http://www.thamehistory.net/topics/ThameHoard.htm Thame Local History, The Thame Hoard]</ref>\n\nIn 1974 the [[M40 motorway]] was extended from [[High Wycombe]] to Chilworth Farm at [[Great Milton]]. Junction 7 at [[Great Milton|Milton Common]] is about {{convert|3|mi|0}} southwest of Thame, giving the town a fast road link to London. In 1990 the M40 extension was completed, giving Thame a fast road link to [[Birmingham]].\n\nIn 1987 [[British Rail]] opened {{rws|Haddenham and Thame Parkway}} station at [[Haddenham, Buckinghamshire|Haddenham]], about {{convert|2|mi|0}} northeast of Thame, on the [[Chiltern Main Line]]. [[Chiltern Railways]] now provides passenger services linking the railway station to High Wycombe, {{rws|London Marylebone}}, {{rws|Banbury}} and {{rws|Birmingham Snow Hill}}. The station has a large car park, a taxi office, and regular buses into Thame.\n\nIn 1991 Thame oil depot closed, and BR dismantled the railway between Thame and Princes Risborough. [[Sustrans]] was allowed to re-use the former trackbed to create the [[Phoenix Trail]] which is part of [[National Cycle Network]] route 57. Reopening the rail line through Thame was an option considered by Chiltern Railways in their plan to open a direct rail route from London Marylebone to Oxford via Princes Risborough in 2015. The cost of reinstating bridges was considered prohibitive.\n\n[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] used Thame many times as a location for the ''[[Midsomer Murders]]'' drama series, representing the fictional town of Causton.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finding Causton |url= http://www.visitmidsomer.com/finding-causton/ |website=Visit Midsomer |accessdate=16 May 2018 |date=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nThe town's two largest employers, [[CPM Group]] and [[Travelodge UK|Travelodge]], both have their head offices on the edge of the town. [[W. Lucy & Co.]] moved its base from Oxford to Thame in 2005.\n\n==Public transport==\nSee above for details of Haddenham and Thame Parkway station. As of 2013 the fastest London Marylebone trains took 36 minutes.\n\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz Citaro BD12 DHK Thame TownHall wide.jpg|thumb|[[Arriva the Shires]] and Z&S buses at the stop outside Thame Town Hall]]\n[[Arriva the Shires]] [[Arriva Sapphire|Sapphire]] bus routes 280 and X8 link [[Oxford railway station]] and Aylesbury ''via'' Thame. Route 280 runs daily and serves [[Wheatley, Oxfordshire|Wheatley]] and [[Haddenham, Buckinghamshire|Haddenham]]. It runs every 20 minutes from Mondays to Saturdays and every 30 minutes on Sundays. Route X8 is an express service that bypasses Wheatley and Haddenham, used to run hourly on a Monday to Friday.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/GetTimetable/?guid=50bb8578-6607-47fb-bfa5-fcbf19118a0b&id=117114&date=180729-181206 |title=Sapphire \u2013 Aylesbury to Oxford via Haddenham (280), Thame and Wheatley (280) |publisher=[[Arriva Shires & Essex]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> From February 2019, the X8 only has 6 buses a day. 2 in the morning peak running from Aylesbury to Oxford and 4 in the evening peak running from Oxford to Aylesbury.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/beds-and-bucks/services/280-x8---sapphire---aylesbury-to-oxford/?direction=outbound |title=Sapphire \u2013 Aylesbury to Oxford via Haddenham (280), Thame and Wheatley (280) |publisher=[[Arriva Shires & Essex]] |accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Carousel Buses]] route 40 links Thame with High Wycombe ''via'' [[Chinnor]] and [[Stokenchurch]]. Services run hourly from Mondays to Saturdays. There is no Sunday or [[Bank holiday#In the United Kingdom|bank holiday]] service.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://assets.goaheadbus.com/media/cms_page_media/2018/2/6/Link40_Timetable_Leaflet_Feb2018-WEB.pdf |title=link40 |publisher=[[Carousel Buses]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016 [[Oxfordshire County Council]] ceased all bus subsidies. [[Buckinghamshire County Council]] still contracts operators to run subsidised bus routes, a few of which link local villages to Thame. They include route 110 operated by Redline Buses<ref>{{cite web |url= http://redlinebuses.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/T-110-Jul-17-1.pdf |title=Aylesbury - Chearsley - Long Crendon - Thame - Worminghall 110 |publisher= Z & S Transport |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> and routes 111, 112 and 113 run by Z&S Transport.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buckscc.gov.uk/media/1634/111.pdf |title=Oakley - Brill - Thame- Aylesbury 111\n |publisher=[[Buckinghamshire County Council]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buckscc.gov.uk/media/1635/112.pdf |title=Upper Winchendon - Oakley - Thame - Bishopstone - Aylesbury 112 |publisher=[[Buckinghamshire County Council]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buckscc.gov.uk/media/1636/113.pdf |title=Oakley - Thame - Longwick - Princes Risborough 113 |publisher=[[Buckinghamshire County Council]] |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Amenities==\n[[File:The Bird Cage Inn, Thame. - geograph.org.uk - 138013.jpg|thumb|Bird Cage, an early 16th-century public house]]\nThame has three primary schools: Barley Hill Primary School,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barley-hill.oxon.sch.uk/ |title=Barley Hill Primary School}}</ref> John Hampden Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.john-hampden.oxon.sch.uk/ |title=John Hampden Primary School}}</ref> and St Joseph's Catholic Primary School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-josephs.oxon.sch.uk/ |title=St Joseph's Catholic Primary School}}</ref> It has one county [[Secondary school#England and Wales|secondary school]], [[Lord Williams's School]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lordwilliams.oxon.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Home&pid=1 |title=Lord Williams's School}}</ref>\n\nThame is home to a wide variety of shops, pubs and restaurants.\n\nThame has a [[Women's Institute]],<ref>{{cite web |url= https://ofwi.weebly.com/list-of-wis.html |title=Alphabetical list of WIs |publisher=Oxfordshire Federation of Women's Institutes |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> a [[Rotary Club]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thame.rotaryweb.org/ |title=Thame Rotary Club}}</ref> and a [[Round Table (club)|Round Table]] club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thameroundtable.org/ |title=Thame & District Round Table}}</ref>\n\nThame hosts the Oxfordshire County and Thame Show, the largest one-day agricultural show in Britain.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thameshow.co.uk/ |title=Thame Show}}</ref> It used to be held on the third Thursday in September, the same day as the three-day Thame Fair opens in the town centre. On the day of the show local schools were closed. In 2010 the show was moved to the last Saturday in July. The organising committee have expressed a wish for the show to be a two-day event in the future.{{citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nIn October a smaller fair is held in the parking area in Upper High Street. In June the Thame Festival is held, which includes a carnival through the main streets, a flower festival, and a fete on the Southern Road recreation area. [[Peter Andre]] attended the Thame Carnival in 2011.\n\n[[File:The Spread Eagle Hotel, Thame - geograph.org.uk - 247563.jpg|thumb|Spread Eagle Hotel, built early in the 18th century]]\nBoth the [[Army Cadet Force|Army Cadets]] and the [[Air Training Corps]] have units in the town. 594 (Thame) Air Training Corps was formed in 1994, originally as a detached flight of 966 (Wallingford) Squadron. It became an independent unit in 1997, taking the number 594 Squadron.\n\nThame has community websites including Thame.\nnet<ref>[http://www.thame.net/ Thame.net]</ref> and Thame Hub.<ref>[http://www.thamehub.co.uk/ Thame Hub]</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n[[Chinnor R.F.C.|Chinnor Rugby Club]] is based at Thame. Its first XV currently plays in [[National Division One]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/chinnor/ |title=Chinnor RFC}}</ref> [[Thame United F.C.|Thame United Football Club]] first team plays in [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] Division One East<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thameunitedfc.demon.co.uk/ |title=Thame United FC}}</ref> Thame Town [[Cricket]] Club first eleven plays in [[Home Counties Premier Cricket League]] Division 2 West.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thametown.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp |title=Thame Town CC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714214303/http://thametown.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp |archivedate=14 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Thame has a [[bowls]] club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thamebowlsclub.co.uk/ |title=Thame Bowls Club}}</ref> and a tennis club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thametennisclub.co.uk/ |title=Thame Tennis Club}}</ref>\n  \n[[The Oxfordshire Golf Club]] is {{convert|1|mi|km}} southwest of Thame. The [[Golf course|course]] was designed by [[Rees Jones]] and has hosted tournaments including the [[Benson & Hedges International Open]] from 1996 until 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoxfordshiregolfclub.com/ |title=The Oxfordshire Golf Club}}</ref>\n\nThame Kickboxing Club, is part of the South East Academy and are based in the sports centre and have trained British, European and World Champions.\n\nThame Runners Club organises the popular Thame 10k each June, 33 years running.\n\n==Twinning==\nThame is twinned with [[Montesson]] in France and [[Sinaia]] in Romania.\n\n==Notable residents==\nViolinist [[Alfredo Campoli]] (1906\u201391) was married at St Joseph's Catholic Church in 1942 and retired to Thame in 1986.<ref name=Campoli>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/campoli.html |title=Alfredo Campoli 1906\u20131991 |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |work=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]]}}</ref> In April 2011 the Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board unveiled a blue plaque at 39 North Street to commemorate him.<ref name=Campoli/>\n\nEnglish film-maker and Internet personality [[Gavin Free]] (born 1988) and his co-host Daniel Gruchy lived in the town from 1992 until 2012. Free now lives in [[Austin, Texas]].<ref name=YouTube>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h9zOaPkyUIE |title=Where We Met |date=30 April 2016 |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Robin Gibb]] of the [[Bee Gees]] and his wife Dwina Murphy-Gibb lived in Prebendal House in Thame until his death in 2012. Robin's younger brother, [[Andy Gibb]], also lived with Robin in Prebendal House in Thame in the weeks before his death in 1988.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thame.net/archives/7767 |title=Thame says 'good bye' to Robin Gibb |work=Thame.net |date=8 June 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[BBC]] actor, announcer, executive [[Harman Grisewood]] (1908\u201397) was brought up at the Prebendal House in the 1910s and 1920s. It had a resident [[Catholic]] priest, Father Randolph Traill, who served in its chapel. In his autobiography, ''One Thing at a Time'' (1968), he described an outing with his brother, nanny, nursemaid and [[baby transport|pram]], when they were stoned by villagers as they approached the [[Church of England parish church]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thamehistory.net/places/Prebendal.htm |work=Thame History |title=The Prebendal}}</ref>\n\nPoet and playwright [[W. B. Yeats]] (1865\u20131939) lived in the town for a short time at Cuttle Brook House, 42 Lower High Street. His son was born there in 1921.<ref>{{cite web |title=Historic Thame Town Trail Factsheet |url=http://www.21stcenturythame.org.uk/files/99999126_THAME%20CENTRE%201%20for%20web.pdf |publisher=21st Century Thame |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902215044/http://www.21stcenturythame.org.uk/files/99999126_THAME%20CENTRE%201%20for%20web.pdf |archivedate=2 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A blue plaque commemorating him was unveiled in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Town unveils four blue plaques|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-13080925|accessdate=16 May 2018|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe composer [[Howard Goodall]] lived in Thame in the 1960s and 70s and, after leaving [[Stowe School]], attended Lord Williams's School.\n\nJonathan More and Matt Black, the duo who make up [[Coldcut]] both lived in Thame and attended LWS.\n\n[[Ronald Lee (cricketer)|Ronald Lee]], cricketer\n\n==See also==\n* [[Thame Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources and further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Aston |first1=Michael |author1-link=Mick Aston |last2=Bond |first2=James |title=The Landscape of Towns |series=Archaeology in the Field Series |year=1976 |publisher=[[J.M. Dent]] & Sons Ltd |place=London |isbn= 0-460-04194-0 |pages= 87, 89, 91, 96, 98 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Lisle |first=Nicola |date=October 2011 |work=[[The Oxford Times|Oxfordshire Limited Edition]] |title=The Master Brewer |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Newsquest]] |pages=81, 83}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Lobel |editor-first=Mary D |editor-link=Mary Lobel |year=1962 |title=A History of the County of Oxford |volume=7: Thame and Dorchester Hundreds |series=[[Victoria County History]] |place=London |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] for the [[Institute of Historical Research]] |pages=160\u2013219 |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Nugent-Grenville |first=George |authorlink=George Nugent-Grenville, 2nd Baron Nugent |year=1854 |title=Some memorials of John Hampden: his party and his times |place=London |publisher=[[Chapman & Hall]] |edition=Third, revised |page=[https://archive.org/details/somememorialsjo02nugegoog/page/n444 361] |url= https://archive.org/details/somememorialsjo02nugegoog |quote=John Hampden Thame. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Page |editor-first=W.H. |editor-link=William Henry Page |year=1907 |title=A History of the County of Oxford |volume=2: Ecclesiastical History, ''etc.'' |series=[[Victoria County History]] |place=Westminster |publisher=[[Archibald Constable]] & Co |pages=83\u201386 |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol2/pp83-86 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sherwood |first1=Jennifer |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Oxfordshire |year=1974 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |place=Harmondsworth |isbn=0-14-071045-0 |pages=806\u2013818 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Thame (England)|Thame}}\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.thame.net Thamedotnet]\n*[http://www.thamehub.co.uk/ Thame Hub]\n*[http://www.thamehistory.net/ Thame Local History]\n*[http://www.gracechurchthame.org.uk Grace Church Thame] \u2013 a [[Newfrontiers]] church\n*[http://www.barleyhillchurch.org.uk Barley Hill Church Thame]\n\n{{South Oxfordshire}}\n{{Oxfordshire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Thame| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:South Oxfordshire District]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c7:5aaa:7601:c5d1:a177:46bc:8194", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Time for jesusb)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thame"}
{"title_page": "Corrie ten Boom", "text_new": "{{Dutch name|ten Boom|Boom}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Corrie ten Boom\n| image = Corrie_ten_Boom_war_heroine.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Cornelia Arnolda Johanna ten Boom\n| birth_date = 15 April 1892\n| birth_place = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|1983|4|15|1892|4|15}}\n| death_place = [[Placentia, California]], U.S.\n| known for = Author of ''[[The Hiding Place (biography)|The Hiding Place]]'', [[Righteous Among the Nations]]\n| occupation = Writer, watchmaker\n| parents       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Casper ten Boom]]\n* Cornelia ten Boom-Luitingh}}\n| relatives = [[Betsie ten Boom]](sister)\nWillem ten Boom( brother)\nNollie ten Boom (sister)\n|website       = [http://www.tenboom.org ten Boom Museum]\n\n}}\n'''Cornelia Arnolda Johanna \"Corrie\" ten Boom''' (15 April 1892 \u2013 15 April 1983) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] watchmaker and later a writer who worked with her father, [[Casper ten Boom]], her sister [[Betsie ten Boom]] and other family members to help many [[Jews]] escape the [[Nazism|Nazis]] from [[the Holocaust]] during [[World War II]] by hiding them in her home. They were caught, and she was arrested and sent to the [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]]. Her most famous book, ''[[The Hiding Place (biography)|The Hiding Place]]'', is a biography that recounts the story of her family's efforts and how she found hope while she was imprisoned at the concentration camp.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:CorrieTenBoom.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Corrie ten Boom c. 1921]]\nCorrie ten Boom was born on 15 April 1892 to a working-class family in [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands, near [[Haarlem]]. Named after her mother, Cornelia, but known as Corrie all her life, she was the youngest child of [[Casper ten Boom]], a jeweler and watchmaker.<ref name=\"auto0\">{{Citation|  url = https://www.biography.com/people/corrie-ten-boom-21358155 | publisher = A&E Television Networks, LLC. | title =  Corrie ten Boom Biography}}</ref> Her father was fascinated by the craft of watchmaking and often became so engrossed in his work that he forgot to charge customers for his services.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=117}}</ref>\n\nShe trained to be a watchmaker herself, and in 1922, she became the first woman to be licensed as a watchmaker in The Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=23970|title=The Watchmaker's Secret Room: Corrie ten Boom, The Holocaust Rescuer Behind \"The Hiding Place\"|website=www.amightygirl.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref> Over the next decade, in addition to working in her father's shop, she established a youth club for teenage girls, which provided religious instruction and classes in the performing arts, sewing, and handicrafts.<ref name=\"auto0\"/> She and her family were [[Calvinism|Calvinist]] [[Christians]] in the [[Dutch Reformed Church]], and their faith inspired them to serve their society, which they did by offering shelter, food and money to those who were in need.<ref name=\"auto0\"/>\n\n==World War II==\n{{Righteous Among the Nations}}\nIn May 1940, the [[Battle of the Netherlands|Germans invaded the Netherlands]]. One of their restrictions was the banning of the youth club.<ref>ten Boom, Corrie. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009</ref>{{Rp | needed = yes | date = March 2013}} In May 1942, a well-dressed woman came to the ten Booms' with a suitcase in hand and told them that she was a [[Judaism|Jew]], her husband had been arrested several months earlier, her son had gone into hiding and Occupation authorities had recently visited her so she was afraid to go back. She heard that the ten Booms had previously helped their Jewish neighbors, the Weils, and asked if they could help her too. Casper  readily agreed that she could stay with them although the police headquarters was only half a block away.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=118}}</ref> A devoted reader of the [[Old Testament]], he believed that the Jews were the \"[[Jews as the chosen people|chosen people]]\" and told the woman, \"In this household, God's people are always welcome\".<ref>Boom, Corrie ten. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009, p. 88</ref> The family then became very active in the [[Dutch resistance|Dutch underground]] hiding refugees and honouring the Jewish [[Shabbat|Sabbath]].<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A622388 | publisher = The British Broadcasting Company | title = DNA | contribution = H2G2}}.</ref> The family never sought to convert any of the Jews who stayed with them.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=119}}</ref>\n\nThus the ten Booms created \"The Hiding Place\" (Dutch: ''De Schuilplaats'' or ''de B\u00e9j\u00e9'', pronounced \"bayay\", an abbreviation of the street , [[Barteljorisstraat]]). Corrie and her sister Betsie opened their home to Jewish and Gentile refugees who were members of the [[Dutch resistance|resistance movement]], and as a result they were sought after by the [[Gestapo]] and its Dutch counterpart. The secret room was in Corrie's bedroom behind a false wall and would hold 6 people. A ventilation system was installed for the occupants. A buzzer could be heard in the house to warn the refugees to get into the room as quickly as possible during security sweeps through the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Corrie ten Boom Biography |url=https://www.biography.com/activist/corrie-ten-boom |website=Biography |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref> They had plenty of room, but wartime shortages meant that food was scarce. Every non-Jewish Dutch person had received a ration card, the requirement for obtaining weekly food coupons. Through her charitable work, ten Boom knew many people in Haarlem and remembered a family with a disabled daughter, whose father was a civil servant who was now in charge of the local ration-card office.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She went to his house one evening, and when he asked how many ration cards she needed, \"I opened my mouth to say, 'Five,'\" ten Boom wrote in ''The Hiding Place''. \"But the number that unexpectedly and astonishingly came out instead was: 'One hundred.'\"<ref>Boom, Corrie ten. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009, p. 92</ref> He gave them to her and she provided cards to every Jew she met.\n\nThe refugee work which ten Boom and her sister did at the Beje became known by the [[Dutch Resistance]], which sent an architect to the ten Boom home to build a secret room adjacent to the room for the Jews who were in hiding and an alert buzzer that could be used to warn the refugees to get into the room as quickly as possible.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n===Arrest, detention and release===\nOn February 28th, 1944, a Dutch informant, Jan Vogel, told the Nazis about the ten Booms' work; at around 12:30 p.m. of that day, the Nazis arrested the entire ten Boom family. They were sent to [[Scheveningen]] Prison when Resistance materials and extra [[ration cards]] were found at the home.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=120}}</ref> Nollie and Willem were released immediately, along with Corrie's nephew Peter; Casper died ten days later. The group of six people hidden by the ten Booms, made up of both Jews and resistance workers, remained undiscovered. Corrie received a letter one day in prison, \"All the watches in your cabinet are safe\", meaning that the refugees had managed to escape and were safe.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> Four days after the raid, resistance workers transferred them to other locations. Altogether, the [[Gestapo]] arrested some 30 people who were in the family home that day.<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10006914 | publisher = The Holocaust Memorial | title = Holocaust Memorial - Corrie ten Boom}}</ref>\n\nTen Boom was initially held in [[solitary confinement]]. After three months, she was taken to her first hearing. At her trial, ten Boom spoke about her work with the mentally disabled; the Nazi lieutenant scoffed, because the Nazis had been [[Aktion T4|killing mentally disabled individuals]] for years in accordance with their [[Nazi eugenics|eugenics]] policies.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=121}}</ref> Ten Boom defended her work by saying that in the eyes of [[God]], a mentally disabled person might be more valuable \"than a watchmaker. Or a lieutenant.\"<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nCorrie and Betsie were sent from Scheveningen to [[Herzogenbusch concentration camp|Herzogenbusch]], a political [[concentration camp]] (also known as Kamp Vught) and finally to the [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]], a women's labor camp in [[Germany]]. There, they held worship services after the hard days at work by using a [[Bible]] that they had managed to smuggle in.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> While they were imprisoned at Ravensbruck, Betsie and her sister began to discuss plans for finding a place of healing after the war. Betsie's health continued to deteriorate, and she died on 16 December 1944 at the age of 59.<ref>{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|pages=121\u2013122}}</ref> Before she died, she told Corrie, \"There is no pit so deep that He [God] is not deeper still.\" Fifteen days later, Corrie was released. Afterwards, she was told that her release was because of a clerical error and that a week later, all the women in her age group were sent to the [[gas chamber]]s.<ref>Boom, Corrie ten. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009, p 240</ref>\n\nCorrie returned home in the midst of the \"[[Dutch famine of 1944\u201345|hunger winter]]\". She still opened her doors to the mentally disabled who were in hiding for fear of execution.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=122}}</ref>\n\n==Life after the war==\nAfter the war, Corrie returned to the Netherlands to set up a [[rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitation]] centre in [[Bloemendaal]]. The refuge housed concentration-camp survivors and exclusively sheltered jobless Dutch who had collaborated with the Germans during the Occupation until 1950, when it accepted anyone in need of care. She returned to Germany in 1946 and met with and forgave two Germans who had been employed at Ravensbr\u00fcck, one of whom had been particularly cruel to Betsie.<ref name=\"auto5\"/> Ten Boom went on to travel the world as a public speaker, appearing in more than 60 countries. She wrote many books during this period.\n\nOne of these books is entitled \u201cTramp for the Lord\u201d and was written in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Each chapter tells a short, different story about her world travels and sharing the Gospel message in Africa, Europe, the Americas, Asia, and even in difficult to reach and dangerous countries such as Russia (then-[[USSR]]), Cuba, and China. It features photographs of Corrie and her important messages of forgiveness, hope, Love, and Salvation through the saving grace of Jesus Christ.\n\nCorrie told the story of her family members and their [[World War II]] work in her bestselling book, ''[[The Hiding Place (biography)|The Hiding Place]]'' (1971), which was made into a 1975 [[World Wide Pictures]] film, ''[[The Hiding Place (film)|The Hiding Place]]'', starring [[Jeannette Clift]] as Corrie and [[Julie Harris (actress)|Julie Harris]] as Betsie. In 1977, the 85-year-old Corrie migrated to [[Placentia, California]]. In 1978, she suffered two [[stroke]]s, the first rendered her unable to speak, and the second resulted in paralysis. She died on her 91st birthday, 15 April 1983, after suffering a third stroke.\n\nA sequel film, ''[[Return to the Hiding Place|Return to the Hiding Place (War of Resistance)]]'', was released in 2011 in the [[United Kingdom]] and in 2013 it was released in the [[United States]]. The film was based on Hans Poley's book, which painted a wider picture of the circle of which she was a part.\n\n==Honors==\n* Israel honored her by naming her [[Righteous Among the Nations]].\n* She was knighted by the Queen of the Netherlands in recognition of her work during the war. \n* The [[Ten Boom Museum]] in Haarlem is dedicated to her and her family in recognition of their work.\n* [[The King's College (New York)|The King's College]] in [[New York City]] named a new women's house in her honor.\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Faith Triumphs | series = Heroes of The Faith | first = Halcyon C. | last = Backhouse | year = 1992 |location=Alton |publisher=Hunt & Thorpe|postscript=. |isbn=1-85608-007-2}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom | series = Chronicles of Faith | first1 = Kjersti Hoff | last1 = Baez |first2=Al |last2=Bohl | year = 2008 |orig-year=1989 |location=Ulrichsville, Ohio |publisher=Barbour Pub |postscript=. |isbn=1-59789-967-4}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Keeper of the Angels' Den | last1 = Benge | first1 = Janet | first2 = Geoffrey \u2018Geoff\u2019 | last2 = Benge | year = 1999 |location=Seattle, WA |publisher=YWAM Pub|postscript=.|isbn=1-57658-136-5}}\n* {{Citation | title = Paint the Prisons Bright: Corrie ten Boom | first = Jill | last = Briscoe | year = 1991|postscript=. |location=Dallas |publisher=Word Pub|isbn=0-8499-3308-0}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie, the Lives She's Touched | first = Joan Winmill | last = Brown |year=1979 |postscript=. |location=Old Tappan, N.J |publisher=F.H. Revell Co|isbn=0-8007-1049-5}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom, Her Life, Her Faith: A Biography | first = Carole C. | last = Carlson |year = 1983|postscript=. |location=Old Tappan, N.J |publisher=F.H. Revell Co|isbn=0-8007-1293-5}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Anywhere He Leads Me | first = Judith | last = Couchman | year = 1997|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Victorious: Corrie ten Boom and The Hiding Place | first = Stan | last = Guthrie | year = 2019| publisher=Paraclete Press|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = The Corrie ten Boom Story: Turning Point | first = David | last = Mainse | year = 1976|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Are All The Watches Safe | first = Catherine | last = McKenzie | year = 2006|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Shining In The Darkness | first1 = Ren\u00e9e | last1 = Meloche | first2 = Bryan | last2 = Pollard | year = 2002|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Seven Women And The Secret To Their Greatness | first = Eric | last = Metaxas | year = 2015 | location = Nashville, TN | publisher = Nelson Books | postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = The Five Silent Years of Corrie ten Boom | first = Pamela Rosewell | last = Moore | year = 1986|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Life Lessons From The Hiding Place: Discovering The Heart of Corrie ten Boom | first = Pamela Rosewell | last = Moore | year = 2004 |postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Return to The Hiding Place | first = Hans | last = Poley | year = 1993|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom Speaks To Prisoners | first = Chaplain | last = Ray | year = 1985|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Faith In Dark Places | first = Sue | last = Shaw | year = 1996|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = A Visit To The Hiding Place: The Life Changing Experiences of Corrie ten Boom | first = Emily S | last = Smith|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = My Years with Corrie | first = Ellen de Kroon |last = Stamps | year = 1978 |location=Old Tappan, N.J |publisher=F.H. Revell Co|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = The Secret Room: The Story of Corrie ten Boom |last=Wallington|first=David| year = 1981 |location=Exeter |publisher=Religious Education Press|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: The Watchmaker's Daughter | first = Jean | last = Watson | year = 1994|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: The Heroine of Haarlem | first = Samuel \u2018Sam\u2019 | last = Wellman | year = 1984|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Heroes of The Faith | first = Samuel \u2018Sam\u2019 | last = Wellman | year = 2004 |postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom | first = Kathleen | last = White | year = 1991|postscript=.}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Corrie ten Boom}}\n* [https://archon.wheaton.edu/?p=collections/controlcard&id=1281 Corrie ten Boom Papers], Billy Graham Center Archives, Wheaton College. \n* [http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4014036 Corrie ten Boom] \u2013 her activity to save Jews' lives during the [[Holocaust]], at [[Yad Vashem]] website\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.hearthasreasons.com/bibliography.php | title = Holocaust Rescuers Bibliography | publisher = Heart has reasons | access-date = 2006-01-01 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131026063357/http://www.hearthasreasons.com/bibliography.php | archive-date = 2013-10-26 | url-status = dead }}.\n* {{Find a Grave|22002|name=Corrie ten Boom}}.\n* {{Citation | url = https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10006914 | title = Corrie ten Boom | place = US | publisher = Holocaust Memorial Museum}}.\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.haarlemshuffle.com/history/topic.php?id=31 | contribution = Corrie ten Boom | title = History | publisher = Haarlem Shuffle}}\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.raoulwallenberg.net/saviors/others/corrie-ten-boom-dutch-savior/ | title = Saviors | contribution = Corrie ten Boom \u2013 a Dutch Savior | publisher = Raoul Wallenberg}}.\n* {{Citation | publisher = Evangelical Bible | url = http://evangelicalbible.com/shop/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=24_30&products_id=156 | title = The Hiding Place | format = DVD}}: a remastered DVD including many of her testimonies.\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.corrietenboomLive.com/ | title = Corrie ten Boom Live}}.\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.readthespirit.com/interfaith_heroes/2009/01/2nd-annual-interfaith-heroes-month-no-24-corrie-ten-boom.html | contribution = Corrie ten Boom, Interfaith Hero | publisher = Read The Spirit | title = 2nd annual interfaith heroes month | number = 24 | date = Jan 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090625101837/http://www.readthespirit.com/interfaith_heroes/2009/01/2nd-annual-interfaith-heroes-month-no-24-corrie-ten-boom.html | archivedate = 2009-06-25 }}.\n* {{Citation|url=http://www.carpsplace.com/spire/hiding |first=Al |last=Hartley |title=The Hiding Place |publisher=Carps place |format=[[PDF]] |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122119/http://www.carpsplace.com/spire/hiding%20place.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-08 }}. \n* {{Citation | url = http://www.passionplayers.org/ | first = Elizabeth | last = Burdick | title = No Pit So Deep: the life and witness of Corrie ten Boom | type = play | publisher = Passion Players | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060324/http://www.passionplayers.org/ | archivedate = 2013-09-21 }}.\n\n{{Righteous footer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boom, Corrie ten}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:Christian writers]]\n[[Category:Dutch emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Dutch members of the Dutch Reformed Church]]\n[[Category:Dutch memoirists]]\n[[Category:Dutch people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Dutch Resistance members]]\n[[Category:Dutch Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Dutch evangelicals]]\n[[Category:Evangelists]]\n[[Category:Herzogenbusch concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:People from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:People from Haarlem]]\n[[Category:Protestant Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Rescue of Jews during the Holocaust]]\n[[Category:Watchmakers (people)]]\n[[Category:Women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Jewish concentration camp survivors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dutch name|ten Boom|Boom}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Corrie ten Boom\n| image = Corrie_ten_Boom_war_heroine.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Cornelia Arnolda Johanna ten Boom\n| birth_date = 15 April 1892\n| birth_place = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|1983|4|15|1892|4|15}}\n| death_place = [[Placentia, California]], U.S.\n| known for = Author of ''[[The Hiding Place (biography)|The Hiding Place]]'', [[Righteous Among the Nations]]\n| occupation = Writer, watchmaker\n| parents       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Casper ten Boom]]\n* Cornelia ten Boom-Luitingh}}\n| relatives = [[Betsie ten Boom]] (sister)\n|website       = [http://www.tenboom.org ten Boom Museum]\n\n}}\n'''Cornelia Arnolda Johanna \"Corrie\" ten Boom''' (15 April 1892 \u2013 15 April 1983) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] watchmaker and later a writer who worked with her father, [[Casper ten Boom]], her sister [[Betsie ten Boom]] and other family members to help many [[Jews]] escape the [[Nazism|Nazis]] from [[the Holocaust]] during [[World War II]] by hiding them in her home. They were caught, and she was arrested and sent to the [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]]. Her most famous book, ''[[The Hiding Place (biography)|The Hiding Place]]'', is a biography that recounts the story of her family's efforts and how she found hope while she was imprisoned at the concentration camp.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:CorrieTenBoom.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Corrie ten Boom c. 1921]]\nCorrie ten Boom was born on 15 April 1892 to a working-class family in [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands, near [[Haarlem]]. Named after her mother, Cornelia, but known as Corrie all her life, she was the youngest child of [[Casper ten Boom]], a jeweler and watchmaker.<ref name=\"auto0\">{{Citation|  url = https://www.biography.com/people/corrie-ten-boom-21358155 | publisher = A&E Television Networks, LLC. | title =  Corrie ten Boom Biography}}</ref> Her father was fascinated by the craft of watchmaking and often became so engrossed in his work that he forgot to charge customers for his services.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=117}}</ref>\n\nShe trained to be a watchmaker herself, and in 1922, she became the first woman to be licensed as a watchmaker in The Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=23970|title=The Watchmaker's Secret Room: Corrie ten Boom, The Holocaust Rescuer Behind \"The Hiding Place\"|website=www.amightygirl.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref> Over the next decade, in addition to working in her father's shop, she established a youth club for teenage girls, which provided religious instruction and classes in the performing arts, sewing, and handicrafts.<ref name=\"auto0\"/> She and her family were [[Calvinism|Calvinist]] [[Christians]] in the [[Dutch Reformed Church]], and their faith inspired them to serve their society, which they did by offering shelter, food and money to those who were in need.<ref name=\"auto0\"/>\n\n==World War II==\n{{Righteous Among the Nations}}\nIn May 1940, the [[Battle of the Netherlands|Germans invaded the Netherlands]]. One of their restrictions was the banning of the youth club.<ref>ten Boom, Corrie. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009</ref>{{Rp | needed = yes | date = March 2013}} In May 1942, a well-dressed woman came to the ten Booms' with a suitcase in hand and told them that she was a [[Judaism|Jew]], her husband had been arrested several months earlier, her son had gone into hiding and Occupation authorities had recently visited her so she was afraid to go back. She heard that the ten Booms had previously helped their Jewish neighbors, the Weils, and asked if they could help her too. Casper  readily agreed that she could stay with them although the police headquarters was only half a block away.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=118}}</ref> A devoted reader of the [[Old Testament]], he believed that the Jews were the \"[[Jews as the chosen people|chosen people]]\" and told the woman, \"In this household, God's people are always welcome\".<ref>Boom, Corrie ten. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009, p. 88</ref> The family then became very active in the [[Dutch resistance|Dutch underground]] hiding refugees and honouring the Jewish [[Shabbat|Sabbath]].<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A622388 | publisher = The British Broadcasting Company | title = DNA | contribution = H2G2}}.</ref> The family never sought to convert any of the Jews who stayed with them.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=119}}</ref>\n\nThus the ten Booms created \"The Hiding Place\" (Dutch: ''De Schuilplaats'' or ''de B\u00e9j\u00e9'', pronounced \"bayay\", an abbreviation of the street , [[Barteljorisstraat]]). Corrie and her sister Betsie opened their home to Jewish and Gentile refugees who were members of the [[Dutch resistance|resistance movement]], and as a result they were sought after by the [[Gestapo]] and its Dutch counterpart. The secret room was in Corrie's bedroom behind a false wall and would hold 6 people. A ventilation system was installed for the occupants. A buzzer could be heard in the house to warn the refugees to get into the room as quickly as possible during security sweeps through the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Corrie ten Boom Biography |url=https://www.biography.com/activist/corrie-ten-boom |website=Biography |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref> They had plenty of room, but wartime shortages meant that food was scarce. Every non-Jewish Dutch person had received a ration card, the requirement for obtaining weekly food coupons. Through her charitable work, ten Boom knew many people in Haarlem and remembered a family with a disabled daughter, whose father was a civil servant who was now in charge of the local ration-card office.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She went to his house one evening, and when he asked how many ration cards she needed, \"I opened my mouth to say, 'Five,'\" ten Boom wrote in ''The Hiding Place''. \"But the number that unexpectedly and astonishingly came out instead was: 'One hundred.'\"<ref>Boom, Corrie ten. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009, p. 92</ref> He gave them to her and she provided cards to every Jew she met.\n\nThe refugee work which ten Boom and her sister did at the Beje became known by the [[Dutch Resistance]], which sent an architect to the ten Boom home to build a secret room adjacent to the room for the Jews who were in hiding and an alert buzzer that could be used to warn the refugees to get into the room as quickly as possible.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n===Arrest, detention and release===\nOn February 28th, 1944, a Dutch informant, Jan Vogel, told the Nazis about the ten Booms' work; at around 12:30 p.m. of that day, the Nazis arrested the entire ten Boom family. They were sent to [[Scheveningen]] Prison when Resistance materials and extra [[ration cards]] were found at the home.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=120}}</ref> Nollie and Willem were released immediately, along with Corrie's nephew Peter; Casper died ten days later. The group of six people hidden by the ten Booms, made up of both Jews and resistance workers, remained undiscovered. Corrie received a letter one day in prison, \"All the watches in your cabinet are safe\", meaning that the refugees had managed to escape and were safe.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> Four days after the raid, resistance workers transferred them to other locations. Altogether, the [[Gestapo]] arrested some 30 people who were in the family home that day.<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10006914 | publisher = The Holocaust Memorial | title = Holocaust Memorial - Corrie ten Boom}}</ref>\n\nTen Boom was initially held in [[solitary confinement]]. After three months, she was taken to her first hearing. At her trial, ten Boom spoke about her work with the mentally disabled; the Nazi lieutenant scoffed, because the Nazis had been [[Aktion T4|killing mentally disabled individuals]] for years in accordance with their [[Nazi eugenics|eugenics]] policies.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=121}}</ref> Ten Boom defended her work by saying that in the eyes of [[God]], a mentally disabled person might be more valuable \"than a watchmaker. Or a lieutenant.\"<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nCorrie and Betsie were sent from Scheveningen to [[Herzogenbusch concentration camp|Herzogenbusch]], a political [[concentration camp]] (also known as Kamp Vught) and finally to the [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]], a women's labor camp in [[Germany]]. There, they held worship services after the hard days at work by using a [[Bible]] that they had managed to smuggle in.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> While they were imprisoned at Ravensbruck, Betsie and her sister began to discuss plans for finding a place of healing after the war. Betsie's health continued to deteriorate, and she died on 16 December 1944 at the age of 59.<ref>{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|pages=121\u2013122}}</ref> Before she died, she told Corrie, \"There is no pit so deep that He [God] is not deeper still.\" Fifteen days later, Corrie was released. Afterwards, she was told that her release was because of a clerical error and that a week later, all the women in her age group were sent to the [[gas chamber]]s.<ref>Boom, Corrie ten. ''The Hiding Place''. Peabody Massachusetts Hendrickson Publishers, 2009, p 240</ref>\n\nCorrie returned home in the midst of the \"[[Dutch famine of 1944\u201345|hunger winter]]\". She still opened her doors to the mentally disabled who were in hiding for fear of execution.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781556529610|page=122}}</ref>\n\n==Life after the war==\nAfter the war, Corrie returned to the Netherlands to set up a [[rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitation]] centre in [[Bloemendaal]]. The refuge housed concentration-camp survivors and exclusively sheltered jobless Dutch who had collaborated with the Germans during the Occupation until 1950, when it accepted anyone in need of care. She returned to Germany in 1946 and met with and forgave two Germans who had been employed at Ravensbr\u00fcck, one of whom had been particularly cruel to Betsie.<ref name=\"auto5\"/> Ten Boom went on to travel the world as a public speaker, appearing in more than 60 countries. She wrote many books during this period.\n\nOne of these books is entitled \u201cTramp for the Lord\u201d and was written in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Each chapter tells a short, different story about her world travels and sharing the Gospel message in Africa, Europe, the Americas, Asia, and even in difficult to reach and dangerous countries such as Russia (then-[[USSR]]), Cuba, and China. It features photographs of Corrie and her important messages of forgiveness, hope, Love, and Salvation through the saving grace of Jesus Christ.\n\nCorrie told the story of her family members and their [[World War II]] work in her bestselling book, ''[[The Hiding Place (biography)|The Hiding Place]]'' (1971), which was made into a 1975 [[World Wide Pictures]] film, ''[[The Hiding Place (film)|The Hiding Place]]'', starring [[Jeannette Clift]] as Corrie and [[Julie Harris (actress)|Julie Harris]] as Betsie. In 1977, the 85-year-old Corrie migrated to [[Placentia, California]]. In 1978, she suffered two [[stroke]]s, the first rendered her unable to speak, and the second resulted in paralysis. She died on her 91st birthday, 15 April 1983, after suffering a third stroke.\n\nA sequel film, ''[[Return to the Hiding Place|Return to the Hiding Place (War of Resistance)]]'', was released in 2011 in the [[United Kingdom]] and in 2013 it was released in the [[United States]]. The film was based on Hans Poley's book, which painted a wider picture of the circle of which she was a part.\n\n==Honors==\n* Israel honored her by naming her [[Righteous Among the Nations]].\n* She was knighted by the Queen of the Netherlands in recognition of her work during the war. \n* The [[Ten Boom Museum]] in Haarlem is dedicated to her and her family in recognition of their work.\n* [[The King's College (New York)|The King's College]] in [[New York City]] named a new women's house in her honor.\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Faith Triumphs | series = Heroes of The Faith | first = Halcyon C. | last = Backhouse | year = 1992 |location=Alton |publisher=Hunt & Thorpe|postscript=. |isbn=1-85608-007-2}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom | series = Chronicles of Faith | first1 = Kjersti Hoff | last1 = Baez |first2=Al |last2=Bohl | year = 2008 |orig-year=1989 |location=Ulrichsville, Ohio |publisher=Barbour Pub |postscript=. |isbn=1-59789-967-4}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Keeper of the Angels' Den | last1 = Benge | first1 = Janet | first2 = Geoffrey \u2018Geoff\u2019 | last2 = Benge | year = 1999 |location=Seattle, WA |publisher=YWAM Pub|postscript=.|isbn=1-57658-136-5}}\n* {{Citation | title = Paint the Prisons Bright: Corrie ten Boom | first = Jill | last = Briscoe | year = 1991|postscript=. |location=Dallas |publisher=Word Pub|isbn=0-8499-3308-0}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie, the Lives She's Touched | first = Joan Winmill | last = Brown |year=1979 |postscript=. |location=Old Tappan, N.J |publisher=F.H. Revell Co|isbn=0-8007-1049-5}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom, Her Life, Her Faith: A Biography | first = Carole C. | last = Carlson |year = 1983|postscript=. |location=Old Tappan, N.J |publisher=F.H. Revell Co|isbn=0-8007-1293-5}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Anywhere He Leads Me | first = Judith | last = Couchman | year = 1997|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Victorious: Corrie ten Boom and The Hiding Place | first = Stan | last = Guthrie | year = 2019| publisher=Paraclete Press|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = The Corrie ten Boom Story: Turning Point | first = David | last = Mainse | year = 1976|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | title = Corrie ten Boom: Are All The Watches Safe | first = Catherine | last = McKenzie | year = 2006|postscript=.}}\n* {{Citation | 